WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.160
[Amit Varma]: The philosopher Thomas Nagel once wrote an essay called What is it like to be a bat?

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:16.760
[Amit Varma]: The essay deals with the nature of consciousness, its deep and nuanced and influential and controversial.

00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:21.840
[Amit Varma]: And my takeaway from it, when I first read it as a kid, was that no matter how much knowledge

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:26.720
[Amit Varma]: we gather, we cannot really know what it is like to be a bat.

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:30.280
[Amit Varma]: Bats navigate the world through something called echolocation. In other words, they

00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:36.000
[Amit Varma]: use sound to see. Now, we can understand this at an intellectual level, using the laws of

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.800
[Amit Varma]: physics and so on, but we can't actually get inside the head of a bat. And why only look

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:46.180
[Amit Varma]: at other species? I would argue that despite being wired for empathy, it is hard for any

00:00:46.180 --> 00:00:51.840
[Amit Varma]: one human to know what it is to be someone else. For example, I'm a man. And no matter

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:57.160
[Amit Varma]: how much knowledge or empathy I have, I can't truly know what it is like to be a woman.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:02.840
[Amit Varma]: To carry that extra layer of awareness every time I enter a lift, or walk on the street

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:09.000
[Amit Varma]: at night, or just sense someone's inclusive gaze on me. Those extra layers would shape

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.120
[Amit Varma]: everything else about me till I wouldn't be me. And that's the whole point.

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:17.560
[Amit Varma]: And this is not just across gender. One of my favourite novelists, Georges Simenon, once

00:01:17.560 --> 00:01:22.560
[Amit Varma]: said that the biggest tragedy in the world was that communication, complete communication

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:28.840
[Amit Varma]: is impossible between any two people in this world. Maybe we can never truly know other

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:33.640
[Amit Varma]: people who remain characters in the grand play in our head. Maybe we can never even

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:38.240
[Amit Varma]: know ourselves, because we are wired to be self delusional. But before I go too far down

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:43.880
[Amit Varma]: that road, let me come to the question that sparked my desire to record this episode.

00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:49.240
[Amit Varma]: For someone born a Hindu in India, is it possible to truly know what it is like to be born a

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:50.240
[Amit Varma]: Muslim?

