00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:28.800
[Amit Varma]: Gazala, hi, welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. Thank you so much. Such a pleasure being here.

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:33.160
[Amit Varma]: I loved reading your book, Born a Muslim. And, you know, one of the sort of things I

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:38.320
[Amit Varma]: really liked about it is how it's such an organic mix of the personal and the socio

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:43.480
[Amit Varma]: political that, you know, through the story of your own life, in a sense, and your experiences,

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:49.680
[Amit Varma]: you're also tracing the history of Islam in India, how it's kind of evolved through the

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:54.720
[Amit Varma]: decades and, you know, what it's like to be Muslim in India today, all of which taught

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:58.480
[Amit Varma]: me a lot. But we'll, let's begin this as you begin your book, you begin your book with

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:03.120
[Amit Varma]: this wonderful introduction, which to me was worth the price of the book alone, which is

00:06:03.120 --> 00:06:07.960
[Amit Varma]: like this long personal essay, which talks about your growing up years and all of that.

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:12.680
[Amit Varma]: But you know, even before that, tell me a little bit about the young Gazala as a kid,

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:17.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, where did you grow up? What kind of person were you? And what were your early

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:21.880
[Amit Varma]: influences? What would you read? Fill me into some of that.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:29.600
[Guest]: I grew up in a small Muslim dominated mahala of Agra. We were a large family living in

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:36.360
[Guest]: a very small house. So there were always too many people and too few rooms. And we had

00:06:36.360 --> 00:06:41.080
[Guest]: to share rooms. So it was understood that girls would be sharing the rooms with their

00:06:41.080 --> 00:06:47.920
[Guest]: aunts and boys would be sharing with their uncles. And there was never enough space for

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:58.280
[Guest]: the kids to play. Since, and it was a joint family, my grandfather had 11 kids, six sons

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:05.680
[Guest]: and actually seven sons and four daughters, one of his sons died early. So and I grew

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:12.160
[Guest]: up with a lot of cousins at home. And we were not allowed to step out of the house because

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:21.120
[Guest]: both my grandfather and my father and his younger siblings felt that they wanted to

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:26.280
[Guest]: give us a different kind of life as opposed to our neighborhood. Our neighborhood was

00:07:26.280 --> 00:07:38.280
[Guest]: largely low middle class. And most of the people were employed in some sort of a family

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:45.200
[Guest]: low level business. So a lot of people were underemployed because all of them were doing

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:50.720
[Guest]: the same thing. So the kids also didn't go to the best of schools, a lot of kids didn't

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:58.120
[Guest]: go to school. So my family, an extended family, they wanted something different for their

00:07:58.120 --> 00:08:06.880
[Guest]: children. We all went to English medium school, I went to a convent school. So to prevent

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:12.520
[Guest]: us from stepping out of the house unescorted or to mingle with the other kids, we used

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:17.120
[Guest]: to be told very fanciful stories about if we go out, somebody would be sitting there

00:08:17.120 --> 00:08:22.680
[Guest]: and he'll be kidnapped or somebody would do some sort of a black magic and we turn into

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:32.400
[Guest]: something else. So that lane outside the house was always full of dangerous possibilities.

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:40.920
[Guest]: And I was not a very brave child. So I was happy staying inside. So we, for us, our play

00:08:40.920 --> 00:08:47.560
[Guest]: area used to be the rooftop where we would spend most of our time. But because I was

00:08:47.560 --> 00:08:54.560
[Guest]: not a very athletic child, I had, I was prone to falling very often and hurting myself,

00:08:54.560 --> 00:09:02.480
[Guest]: especially my ankles. So I was not heavily into a lot of physical games that my other

00:09:02.480 --> 00:09:10.240
[Guest]: cousins would play. And I got more interested because we didn't have any technology, no

00:09:10.240 --> 00:09:20.560
[Guest]: television at home. So we, I drifted into reading and I had this huge desire to just

00:09:20.560 --> 00:09:25.240
[Guest]: read because it was so entertaining that I used to read anything I could lay my hands

00:09:25.240 --> 00:09:32.680
[Guest]: on. I would read the newspaper, whatever I could make of it. I would read textbooks of

00:09:32.680 --> 00:09:39.680
[Guest]: my younger aunts and my uncles. I would read that salacious magazines that my uncle was

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:45.080
[Guest]: subscribing to a Hindi magazine called Manohar Kahania. So whatever I could figure out or

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:50.560
[Guest]: make of it, I used to hide in some corner of the house. Most of the time it used to

00:09:50.560 --> 00:09:57.200
[Guest]: be below the staircase because nobody would be able to see me there. So I would just sit

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:02.680
[Guest]: there, read, or maybe go to the rooftop with everybody else. And while the other kids would

00:10:02.680 --> 00:10:09.140
[Guest]: be playing, I would sit with one of the books in the corner. Came to such a pass that my

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:15.040
[Guest]: mother was very worried about me, about what kind of stuff I was reading. So if I was found

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:19.880
[Guest]: with something in my hand, she would immediately confiscate and check what I was doing because

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:26.400
[Guest]: I would just pick up anything randomly and start reading. And along with that, I also

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:32.320
[Guest]: developed sort of a desire that I also want to write what I was reading. I should be able

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:40.480
[Guest]: to produce something like this. So writing happened concurrently. It was earlier I couldn't

00:10:40.480 --> 00:10:49.200
[Guest]: write prose or something, so I would dabble into some stupid poetry. And so all this was

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:56.040
[Guest]: going on. Finally, I started writing or thinking about writing a little more seriously when

00:10:56.040 --> 00:11:03.720
[Guest]: my father once asked me to write something. He used to come to Delhi very frequently because

00:11:03.720 --> 00:11:12.080
[Guest]: my father was an exporter and a lot of business associates. And he used to export to the state

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:17.000
[Guest]: trading corporation. So their office was in Delhi. So he had to come to Delhi quite often

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:24.760
[Guest]: to meet the bureaucrats, the government officials there. So often we used to come with him because

00:11:24.760 --> 00:11:30.840
[Guest]: it was not a long journey. It would just take about four to five hours in an ambassador

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:38.280
[Guest]: car. So we used to come here and that's when sometimes he would go to Palika Bazaar and

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:46.120
[Guest]: pick up something. And from Hindi, I switched a little to English, you know, kids' magazines

00:11:46.120 --> 00:11:58.160
[Guest]: like Tinkle or very basic stuff like that. So on our journey back to Agra, after one

00:11:58.160 --> 00:12:04.320
[Guest]: such trip, there was a huge procession and we had to take a detour from the main road

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:12.480
[Guest]: and we went through the old city to come to our house in the mahala. And I saw a huge

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:18.200
[Guest]: procession there moving with a statue and I asked my father what it was. So he explained

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:25.080
[Guest]: to me that was Dr. Ambedkar's statue and the procession was being led by his followers

00:12:25.080 --> 00:12:32.240
[Guest]: and they're taking it for, putting it there outside the Agra fort. They were setting it

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:38.080
[Guest]: up there. They had built a small park there where the statue was to be set up. And then

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:43.000
[Guest]: obviously I was curious who Dr. Ambedkar was. So he told me the entire story of his life,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:48.360
[Guest]: how he was a low caste, he had to sit outside the classroom and how despite all that because

00:12:48.360 --> 00:12:55.160
[Guest]: he was so diligent, he worked so hard, he became such a huge personality that he actually

00:12:55.160 --> 00:12:59.240
[Guest]: wrote the constitution. I mean, he told me he wrote the constitution. It's much later

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:05.160
[Guest]: that you realize what he did. So once we reached home, he asked me to write it down for him

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:12.160
[Guest]: to see if I have understood correctly. And over the next two, three days, I wrote whatever

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:20.200
[Guest]: I remembered in a very haphazard sort of English, because English was not my, neither of us

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:25.840
[Guest]: first language. And we also didn't speak English at home. So whatever language I knew, I knew

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:34.240
[Guest]: it from the school. So I wrote it down a few 10, 15 sentences and showed it to my father.

00:13:34.240 --> 00:13:41.200
[Guest]: He was very happy. That encouraged me a lot. I thought I have some potential as a writer.

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:48.960
[Guest]: Few days later, there was this incident of two gangsters, Ranga and Billa, kidnapping

00:13:48.960 --> 00:13:58.160
[Guest]: these siblings, Sanjay and Geeta. And this was all over the newspapers. We used to get

00:13:58.160 --> 00:14:05.560
[Guest]: Amar Jala at home and I read the headlines. I read a little bit of the news. And I asked

00:14:05.560 --> 00:14:13.480
[Guest]: my father what this incident was about. So he explained it to me. And again, he asked

00:14:13.480 --> 00:14:18.720
[Guest]: me, why don't you write it down? So then I wrote it down. And I tried to copy the newspaper

00:14:18.720 --> 00:14:26.120
[Guest]: style of writing it, like intro, just summarizing what happened and then giving a little detail.

00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:35.520
[Guest]: So that's how I was writing concurrently as I was reading. But my reading was not really

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:43.840
[Guest]: literature. It was reading of the papers which were coming home, reading of some stray magazines

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:51.880
[Guest]: and just whatever I could lay my hands on. That was also the time our family was, you

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:58.840
[Guest]: know, we were moving up the ladder of economic prosperity. So things were gradually changing

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:09.360
[Guest]: at home. So my access to a lot of things were also improving gradually. Subsequently, we

00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:16.280
[Guest]: moved from this house to another house that my father was building. We were a nuclear

00:15:16.280 --> 00:15:23.240
[Guest]: family now, except that my younger uncle had come to stay with us. And here all of us had

00:15:23.240 --> 00:15:27.880
[Guest]: our own rooms. There were attached bathrooms, which was a huge luxury. I had never imagined

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:34.120
[Guest]: something like this. We'd only seen it in hotels. And my father had gone and set up

00:15:34.120 --> 00:15:41.800
[Guest]: a place with bathtubs in each bathroom. So it was again a huge luxury. And very ambitiously,

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:48.720
[Guest]: he had built a study in this house. I'll just take you back a little bit. And my father

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:57.640
[Guest]: himself was not a school educated person. His learning of the languages was also self

00:15:57.640 --> 00:16:04.720
[Guest]: tutored. And my mother also just did class 11, and then she got married. So basically,

00:16:04.720 --> 00:16:13.960
[Guest]: my family was not a very educated family. We came from a working class background, despite

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:20.200
[Guest]: the fact that in the caste, Muslim caste hierarchy or class hierarchy, we were number two from

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:27.760
[Guest]: the top. But in terms of education, because my grandfather, his family, they were quite

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:36.520
[Guest]: poor. And most of them were artisans. So it was more important for them to know a trade.

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:43.520
[Guest]: So my grandfather knew the trade of footwear, the upper of the shoe. They used to do that

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:50.440
[Guest]: stitching of the uppers. So that is what he had learned. And my father also started like

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:55.840
[Guest]: that. He started working in a factory as a person who would cut the upper and then subsequently

00:16:55.840 --> 00:17:03.480
[Guest]: he became a supervisor. And eventually he started his own factory. But his desire to

00:17:03.480 --> 00:17:08.520
[Guest]: learn and he was very fascinated by English language. So he had approached a munshi in

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:13.520
[Guest]: the factory who used to do the accounting of, you know, he used to distribute the weekly

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:18.040
[Guest]: wages. So he advised my father that one of the easy ways of learning the language is

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:23.080
[Guest]: that my father could read Urdu. So he said, you subscribe to a Urdu newspaper and you

00:17:23.080 --> 00:17:28.960
[Guest]: subscribe to an English newspaper. And if they are from the same organizations, the

00:17:28.960 --> 00:17:33.640
[Guest]: news would be identical. So you could read it in Urdu and then you could try and read

00:17:33.640 --> 00:17:39.800
[Guest]: in English. So he helped my father with alphabets. And my father then started reading Komi Awas

00:17:39.800 --> 00:17:47.240
[Guest]: and National Herald. Both of them came from the National Herald group of papers. So he

00:17:47.240 --> 00:17:56.560
[Guest]: has own learning was, it was self-tutored. So when we moved to the new house and my father

00:17:56.560 --> 00:18:05.040
[Guest]: built his study, he had no exposure to literature really. And he had no references as to what

00:18:05.040 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest]: he should buy and what he should put in his study. So he used to come to Delhi and he

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:15.800
[Guest]: used to make a special trip during the Delhi Book Fair and just pick up books which looked

00:18:15.800 --> 00:18:22.120
[Guest]: good or books which had some nice blurb or if somebody recommended to him. So it was

00:18:22.120 --> 00:18:29.840
[Guest]: a very eclectic kind of collection and very little fiction there because he obviously

00:18:29.840 --> 00:18:34.440
[Guest]: thought if he's spending so much money on books, the books should give him something

00:18:34.440 --> 00:18:39.400
[Guest]: in return. I mean, he should be able to learn something. So there was a lot of history,

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:48.760
[Guest]: a lot of modern Indian history. Authors like Dominic LePere, Larry Collins, because he

00:18:48.760 --> 00:18:55.560
[Guest]: thought their language was very beautiful, very evocative. Then he used to buy books

00:18:55.560 --> 00:19:02.880
[Guest]: in bulk. So we had the full collection of Patel's biography by, I'm forgetting the name

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:07.960
[Guest]: of the author now. Then the entire collection of Nehru, collection of Gandhi. So that is

00:19:07.960 --> 00:19:14.920
[Guest]: how, what the study was. So when I started reading books, it was, my introduction was

00:19:14.920 --> 00:19:19.320
[Guest]: through nonfiction. So I was reading a lot of historical books. I was reading a lot of

00:19:19.320 --> 00:19:29.040
[Guest]: biographies. I drifted to fiction much, much later in life and I was already 13 or 14 years

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:38.040
[Guest]: old when I started reading novels. And by this time, girls my age had already gone past

00:19:38.040 --> 00:19:43.600
[Guest]: Enid Blyton's and Nancy Drew. So I never really grew up reading them. I probably read one

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:53.200
[Guest]: odd book of this and that, but I then moved to other authors. And so, and alongside this,

00:19:53.200 --> 00:20:02.400
[Guest]: I started fancying myself as a poet because I thought that I was introduced to Urdu poetry

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:08.120
[Guest]: through my parents. They were heavily into poetry. So I couldn't read Urdu, but I used

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:13.680
[Guest]: to ask my mother if she could read out verses to me in Urdu. Or I would nag my father to

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:20.040
[Guest]: read out passages from Maulana Azad's Khubare Khater, where he's talking about his experience

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:29.480
[Guest]: in the jail. So all this drew me to Urdu and I somehow was very attracted to the style

00:20:29.480 --> 00:20:36.000
[Guest]: of Ghazals. And even though I didn't understand a lot of it, I just loved the sound of it.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:42.280
[Guest]: And I used to memorize verses and recite them to myself. So my parents thought that maybe

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:51.000
[Guest]: I can be a poet. So Urdu teacher was appointed and he was also a poet. So he started teaching

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:58.800
[Guest]: me Urdu poetry. And I started writing a few verses in Urdu, which I thought was very bad.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:07.240
[Guest]: And finally, I realized that I am terrible as a poet. And I was embarrassed of my own

00:21:07.240 --> 00:21:17.720
[Guest]: verses, which I wrote. And around that time, I think I came back to English writing. And

00:21:17.720 --> 00:21:27.140
[Guest]: I started writing some sort of a long form of writing, just putting together in a nonsense

00:21:27.140 --> 00:21:32.640
[Guest]: ideas which would come to me or sitting in my study, looking out of the window. So I

00:21:32.640 --> 00:21:38.960
[Guest]: would just write a descriptive essay sort of a thing, a short piece, just describing

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:48.880
[Guest]: that moment. Maybe what helped in this was I was a huge daydreamer. I had never been

00:21:48.880 --> 00:21:55.160
[Guest]: bored of my own company. I never ever said this to anybody that I'm getting bored. If

00:21:55.160 --> 00:22:00.360
[Guest]: I had nothing to do, I would just sit idle and daydream and just imagine things happening

00:22:00.360 --> 00:22:08.360
[Guest]: to me, imagine things happening around me. And I could spend hours doing just that and

00:22:08.360 --> 00:22:15.000
[Guest]: not be bothered at all. So when I started writing, a lot of my writing, my trial and

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:22.360
[Guest]: error sort of writing used to be just describing a particular scene that I was either imagining

00:22:22.360 --> 00:22:29.680
[Guest]: or witnessing. So that is how I was when I was growing up. And I didn't have too many

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:37.080
[Guest]: friends. I didn't make too many friends. So I don't want to say that I was a lonely or

00:22:37.080 --> 00:22:44.280
[Guest]: I preferred being on my own. But I did like to be on my own a lot of times. And even if

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:53.720
[Guest]: I was with friends, as I was growing older, I often wanted to just come back and sit in

00:22:53.720 --> 00:23:00.440
[Guest]: my room and just be on my own. And probably that was one of the reasons because I had

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:04.360
[Guest]: my own attached bathroom. I used to spend a lot of time in my bathroom because nobody

00:23:04.360 --> 00:23:10.600
[Guest]: would disturb me there. So I would just lock myself in there and sit there for a long time.

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:15.840
[Amit Varma]: So that is what it was growing up. Yeah, there is so much to unpack there. And

00:23:15.840 --> 00:23:20.240
[Amit Varma]: just from sort of what you said right now, there's so much that I want to talk about.

00:23:20.240 --> 00:23:25.320
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of you know, before we get to the personal narrative of how events unfolded

00:23:25.320 --> 00:23:29.040
[Amit Varma]: around you and your family and all of that, I'd like to stay with reading a bit like first

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:34.960
[Amit Varma]: of all, all this makes me very sort of nostalgic, because you know, younger people today don't

00:23:34.960 --> 00:23:38.600
[Amit Varma]: realize what a joy it was to read anything that you could get your hand on back in those

00:23:38.600 --> 00:23:42.600
[Amit Varma]: days when you didn't have the internet and the world of information at your fingertips.

00:23:42.600 --> 00:23:47.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I think, you know, a defining image for all Indian kids growing up in the 80s

00:23:47.160 --> 00:23:52.240
[Amit Varma]: would be the one that you described of yourself sitting under the stairs reading Manohar Khania,

00:23:52.240 --> 00:23:59.080
[Amit Varma]: which is, to me, you know, the story of so many people just sort of in one image, what

00:23:59.080 --> 00:24:05.320
[Amit Varma]: also kind of strikes me is the multilingual nature of how you were coming up like one

00:24:05.320 --> 00:24:10.160
[Amit Varma]: thing that I've realized is that, you know, being from a fairly like I was from a fairly

00:24:10.160 --> 00:24:15.480
[Amit Varma]: privileged background. And though in one sense, it was a restriction in the sense that everything

00:24:15.480 --> 00:24:20.040
[Amit Varma]: I read was essentially in English, I read a little bit of Hindi here and there I did

00:24:20.040 --> 00:24:23.920
[Amit Varma]: well in school and all that in Hindi, but all my reading was English. Many of the people

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:29.520
[Amit Varma]: I later encountered in working life, were also people who grew up reading English newspapers,

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:34.800
[Amit Varma]: English books got everything from English. And in a certain sense, that limited their

00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:39.360
[Amit Varma]: worldview. This is a theme I've explored with earlier guests in episodes, I think it came

00:24:39.360 --> 00:24:44.440
[Amit Varma]: up when I was chatting with Akshay Mukul, Rahul Verma, both of whom also read in Hindi

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:49.400
[Amit Varma]: while growing up. And number one, did you feel that being multilingual like this reading

00:24:49.400 --> 00:24:56.360
[Amit Varma]: these multiple languages, Hindi, Urdu, English, that it kind of that your vision was broader

00:24:56.360 --> 00:25:00.480
[Amit Varma]: than say, maybe the people you would subsequently work with in journalism or whatever that you

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:05.960
[Amit Varma]: had seen things that they would not have known or expected, because many of us English speaking

00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:09.760
[Amit Varma]: elites are kind of, you know, in our little bubbles, and we don't really see the world

00:25:09.760 --> 00:25:14.800
[Amit Varma]: outside. But you had, of course, through growing up, you had gotten a glimpse of that, but

00:25:14.800 --> 00:25:19.920
[Amit Varma]: also through languages. And I'll wait for you to answer this, because there's a related

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:24.520
[Amit Varma]: question, which also fascinates me, which has to do with language. But, you know, what's

00:25:24.520 --> 00:25:31.280
[Guest]: your take on this? You know, this exposure to different languages, it was not just a

00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:38.440
[Guest]: question of language, it was a question of different world altogether. Hindi, as I was

00:25:38.440 --> 00:25:43.960
[Guest]: used to go through the textbooks of my aunt, I became familiar with writings of Premchand

00:25:43.960 --> 00:25:51.760
[Guest]: at a very young age, probably even at a time when I was not intelligent enough to grasp

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:57.400
[Guest]: the depth of what he was writing, but I could read and I could see a completely different

00:25:57.400 --> 00:26:07.000
[Guest]: world. Or writers like, you know, Hindi versions of Manto. Now, it was hugely shocking, his

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:13.160
[Guest]: work for a child to be reading that it was really a completely different sort of a idiom,

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:19.600
[Guest]: a completely different sort of imagery that would conjure up in your head. So I felt that

00:26:19.600 --> 00:26:28.960
[Guest]: I was exposed to a variety of things, which when I came to Delhi, and I was exposed to

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:35.360
[Guest]: entirely the English speaking group of friends in my college, and subsequently when I started

00:26:35.360 --> 00:26:41.000
[Guest]: working, they were not exposed to this. So when I would talk to them, they would be talking

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:51.360
[Guest]: about Chekhov, and I would, I had read Chekhov in life, but my understanding, I mean, I could

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:57.600
[Guest]: relate to that poverty part of it, because I had some, that I had seen any poverty, I

00:26:57.600 --> 00:27:02.400
[Guest]: didn't. I was privileged in the sense that by the time I was growing up, my family had

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:10.520
[Guest]: resources. But having read this, I could understand, I could make the connection. Probably another

00:27:10.520 --> 00:27:15.200
[Guest]: thing I would want to add here is it's not just the languages in the novels or in the

00:27:15.200 --> 00:27:22.000
[Guest]: books, it's also the languages of the newspapers. And I would come back to the newspaper for

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:29.480
[Guest]: the simple reason, as a journalist, my exposure to newspaper writing in India has been greater.

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:36.200
[Guest]: And I have seen how newspapers have evolved in India since the mid 80s onwards. Mid 80s

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:42.760
[Guest]: was the time when I was in my teens, and I was reading the newspapers on a very regular

00:27:42.760 --> 00:27:52.600
[Guest]: basis. I'll give you a small example. In the 80s, probably there was a government directive

00:27:52.600 --> 00:27:58.920
[Guest]: that if there was a communal riot or a violence somewhere, the communities would not be identified.

00:27:58.920 --> 00:28:04.520
[Guest]: So it was all, the newspaper reports would say one community has rioted and the second

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:09.040
[Guest]: community reacted. Then the police opened fire and four members of one community have.

00:28:09.040 --> 00:28:16.280
[Guest]: So they would be like that, very vague. I always was curious, who are these communities?

00:28:16.280 --> 00:28:21.160
[Guest]: Who was the instigator? Who started the riot? Who were the people killed? But the English

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:26.600
[Guest]: newspapers would not put this out, maybe out of the government order or out of deference

00:28:26.600 --> 00:28:33.160
[Guest]: for sentiments or whatever. But the Hindi newspaper were very clever. They, papers like

00:28:33.160 --> 00:28:40.360
[Guest]: Amarajala, Adenik, they would say Bahusankhyak, which is majority, and they would say Alpsankhyak.

00:28:40.360 --> 00:28:46.360
[Guest]: So you would know which community has done what. So they were cutting across the government

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:53.600
[Guest]: directive in a very clever way. The Urdu newspapers would identify. They would identify the victims

00:28:53.600 --> 00:28:58.800
[Guest]: by, not by the community, but by names. So you knew that in the police firing, Javed

00:28:58.800 --> 00:29:04.640
[Guest]: and Saje that so and so have died. So they were actually short circuiting the government.

00:29:04.640 --> 00:29:12.320
[Guest]: So I realised that the English journalism, for the sake of being fair and not instigating

00:29:12.320 --> 00:29:19.720
[Guest]: more violence or whatever the principles, was only conveying half a story. So as a reference

00:29:19.720 --> 00:29:27.600
[Guest]: to a particular event, you would not get the correct picture. Whereas the vernacular would

00:29:27.600 --> 00:29:34.640
[Guest]: give you in some way, it would, it would manage to convey the actual story. The other thing

00:29:34.640 --> 00:29:40.960
[Guest]: was that in English journalism, it was said that, you know, the reporter should be invisible.

00:29:40.960 --> 00:29:47.440
[Guest]: You know, you should not show yourself because that invisibility ensures or it was meant

00:29:47.440 --> 00:29:54.560
[Guest]: to ensure some kind of impartiality. But in the vernacular writing, the reporter would

00:29:54.560 --> 00:30:00.160
[Guest]: be invisible, but reporter's bias would be very, very obvious. So it was, when I was

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:08.000
[Guest]: growing up, even then in Agra, I was conscious of the fact that this particular reporter,

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:14.600
[Guest]: if he's saying this, there is a lot of exaggeration in a certain report. So you don't have to

00:30:14.600 --> 00:30:20.160
[Guest]: show yourself up, but your bias shows. So when I come to Delhi and I was studying in

00:30:20.160 --> 00:30:29.760
[Guest]: college and I used to interact with my classmates, I realized that our sensibilities and sensitivity

00:30:29.760 --> 00:30:35.680
[Guest]: towards our environment were very, very different. For example, another example, this Mandal

00:30:35.680 --> 00:30:43.480
[Guest]: agitation was at its peak when I joined college. And I found that most of my classmates were

00:30:43.480 --> 00:30:50.840
[Guest]: actually just repeating what probably they had heard at home and their anger, their rage

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:59.480
[Guest]: against the recommendations was not really reflective of what the truth or the history

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:11.200
[Guest]: of India has been. So I was amazed that this sort of a privileged overhang over these people,

00:31:11.200 --> 00:31:20.240
[Guest]: how much it enables prejudice, how much it is a factor in encouraging a biased view of

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:29.200
[Guest]: your own society. So there's another thing, because of this exposure to multilingual writing,

00:31:29.200 --> 00:31:37.400
[Guest]: both in books and newspapers, I also felt that now when everybody talks about Ganga

00:31:37.400 --> 00:31:45.880
[Guest]: Jamuni and people talk about Ganga Jamuni culture of North India, especially the UP,

00:31:45.880 --> 00:31:54.840
[Guest]: Bihar and parts of Northern Madhya Pradesh, people who have not seen this through literature,

00:31:54.840 --> 00:32:03.280
[Guest]: through writings of a certain period, they assume what the culture would be. See, if

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:12.360
[Guest]: you read short stories by Premchand, you would realize that it was not just celebrating each

00:32:12.360 --> 00:32:19.080
[Guest]: other's festivals. It was not just going to somebody's house on Eid or Diwali. There was

00:32:19.080 --> 00:32:25.200
[Guest]: so much of economic interdependence. The characters were organic, but irrespective of religion,

00:32:25.200 --> 00:32:29.960
[Guest]: characters used to be organic with the stories because that is how a small town or rural

00:32:29.960 --> 00:32:37.280
[Guest]: India lived. There was so much of social and economic engagement with each other. So now

00:32:37.280 --> 00:32:42.600
[Guest]: a lot of people when they talk about, oh, but we always greeted our Muslim friends on

00:32:42.600 --> 00:32:48.360
[Guest]: Eid or our Hindu friends, we played Holi with them. That's just one and probably a superficial

00:32:48.360 --> 00:32:54.720
[Guest]: part of it. It doesn't really convey the kind of dependence you had on each other, the kind

00:32:54.720 --> 00:32:59.280
[Guest]: of trust you had on each other. I'm sorry if I'm giving too many examples. Can I give

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:00.280
[Guest]: one more example?

00:33:00.280 --> 00:33:04.440
[Amit Varma]: Please, please go ahead. There's no such thing as too many examples.

00:33:04.440 --> 00:33:14.280
[Guest]: You know, I had met one gentleman in Delhi while I was working on my book, but I had,

00:33:14.280 --> 00:33:21.400
[Guest]: he was from Farooqabad. So he was narrating the incident of when he was growing up there.

00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:28.160
[Guest]: His family lived in a village where the majority in the village were not Muslims. And his family

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:33.440
[Guest]: was among the two or three Muslim families in that village. But whenever anybody went

00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:39.320
[Guest]: out of the village to visit somewhere or go on a holiday, irrespective of religion, such

00:33:39.320 --> 00:33:45.160
[Guest]: was the stature of this person's father, that he used to, everybody, whoever was going would

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:50.680
[Guest]: leave the house keys, leave the cattle, everything with this family, that you please take care

00:33:50.680 --> 00:33:56.080
[Guest]: of our cattle, you take care of our house while you're away. So that was the level of

00:33:56.080 --> 00:34:04.040
[Guest]: trust and that was the lived heritage of those people, that community, irrespective of religion.

00:34:04.040 --> 00:34:10.280
[Guest]: So this is something which you will, you know, if you are either from this area, or you have

00:34:10.280 --> 00:34:16.280
[Guest]: the sensibility to see it, even if it's not very obvious.

00:34:16.280 --> 00:34:20.680
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating. Again, there's a lot to unpack here. You know, all of these answers of yours

00:34:20.680 --> 00:34:24.600
[Amit Varma]: are like little Chinese boxes, you open one layer, and there's another layer below that,

00:34:24.600 --> 00:34:28.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, so before we get to kind of the subject at hand, and what you've written about

00:34:28.360 --> 00:34:32.800
[Amit Varma]: in your book, you know, I'll just take one more digression with due apology to my listeners,

00:34:32.800 --> 00:34:36.720
[Amit Varma]: because it's a subject that fascinates me. And it again has to do with language. So now

00:34:36.720 --> 00:34:40.760
[Amit Varma]: I teach this online writing course. And a few months back, you know, one of the girls

00:34:40.760 --> 00:34:47.480
[Amit Varma]: who was doing that, who had this very sharp way of observing things, but the language

00:34:47.480 --> 00:34:52.200
[Amit Varma]: was a little not quite formed yet. And she kind of came to me with a problem. And she

00:34:52.200 --> 00:34:56.480
[Amit Varma]: said, you know, the thing is, English is not my first language. So I'm having trouble kind

00:34:56.480 --> 00:35:02.160
[Amit Varma]: of expressing it. And what can I do? And at that point, I remembered, author I had discovered

00:35:02.160 --> 00:35:07.240
[Amit Varma]: called Agatha Christophe, like I'd watched an interview of Jhumpa Lahiri by Tyler Cowen.

00:35:07.240 --> 00:35:11.440
[Amit Varma]: And I link all of these from the show notes. And what Lahiri had done was, her languages

00:35:11.440 --> 00:35:15.080
[Amit Varma]: are English and Bengali, but she learned Italian from scratch. And then she wrote a book in

00:35:15.080 --> 00:35:18.720
[Amit Varma]: Italian. So as an adult, you're learning a whole new language, and you're writing a book

00:35:18.720 --> 00:35:24.240
[Amit Varma]: in that. So when Tyler asked her about that, she pointed to the example of Agatha Christophe,

00:35:24.240 --> 00:35:30.040
[Amit Varma]: who essentially I think, during the war, shifted as an adult to France from somewhere maybe

00:35:30.040 --> 00:35:34.900
[Amit Varma]: Hungary or wherever, I don't remember, but shifted to France, learned French at the age

00:35:34.900 --> 00:35:40.240
[Amit Varma]: of 2021. And then wrote a series of incredible books in French, a completely new language

00:35:40.240 --> 00:35:46.520
[Amit Varma]: to her. So I recommended to this, the participant in my course that why don't you try reading

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:52.320
[Amit Varma]: Agatha Christophe, because her language is very sparse, very powerful, and all of that.

00:35:52.320 --> 00:35:56.720
[Amit Varma]: And she recently told me a few months after I gave her the record, that one, she loved

00:35:56.720 --> 00:36:02.440
[Amit Varma]: those books. And two, what she started doing was that she started, you know, copying from

00:36:02.440 --> 00:36:07.960
[Amit Varma]: the book in the sense writing each sentence again by hand, to get a closer sense of what

00:36:07.960 --> 00:36:13.200
[Amit Varma]: the language was like. And that struck me as something beautiful and inspiring. Because

00:36:13.200 --> 00:36:19.200
[Amit Varma]: what it means is that you're looking at the language with, you know, so to say, gehraayi

00:36:19.200 --> 00:36:24.640
[Amit Varma]: and nazdiki, which you otherwise don't, because we people, like I take English for granted,

00:36:24.640 --> 00:36:29.120
[Amit Varma]: I have to remind myself to be mindful and, you know, go word by word, notice all the

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:34.600
[Amit Varma]: little intricacies of it. But because she was kind of new to it, she was doing this

00:36:34.600 --> 00:36:38.600
[Amit Varma]: and it struck me as such a beautiful thing to do. And therefore, I want to ask that,

00:36:38.600 --> 00:36:43.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, you mentioned that you, at one point, you were drawn to poetry. And it again, struck

00:36:43.480 --> 00:36:49.760
[Amit Varma]: me that, you know, anyone who is, for example, exposed to Urdu, would turn to poetry because

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:54.840
[Amit Varma]: Urdu is such a beautiful lyrical language, you know, English almost seems like a functional

00:36:54.840 --> 00:37:01.120
[Amit Varma]: kind of dry language compared to that. So your experience in these different languages,

00:37:01.120 --> 00:37:05.440
[Amit Varma]: do you think, in some ways, it shaped the book you write? Like, you know, everything

00:37:05.440 --> 00:37:12.160
[Amit Varma]: that you've written is obviously very accomplished. No one can tell that English is sort of not

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:17.200
[Amit Varma]: your mother tongue in that sense. So, you know, did you ever during the course of your

00:37:17.200 --> 00:37:23.000
[Amit Varma]: time, pay that kind of attention to language growing up? Maybe, you know, like everybody,

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:27.040
[Amit Varma]: of course, as I get into journalism and writing will pay attention to craft, they learn to

00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:32.880
[Amit Varma]: edit, they learn to do all of that. But did you feel that there was some, you know, element

00:37:32.880 --> 00:37:37.200
[Amit Varma]: of looking deeper at the language while you were writing in it?

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:43.040
[Guest]: Actually, no, I think language, or writing in English came very naturally to me, I have

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:49.160
[Guest]: no idea how. Even when I was writing grammatically incorrect English, my tenses would be a bit

00:37:49.160 --> 00:37:59.320
[Guest]: heavier. I was always able to put the imagery that I was thinking what I was looking at

00:37:59.320 --> 00:38:07.600
[Guest]: on paper. When I was in first year college, some like, I think the general elections announced

00:38:07.600 --> 00:38:14.160
[Guest]: and I had gone to Agra. And I saw this, I'm forgetting the name of the candidate, Nihal

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:22.600
[Guest]: Singh or somebody. I saw an entourage of this guy. During the campaign, I was driving on

00:38:22.600 --> 00:38:27.840
[Guest]: the highway and just short of Agra, there was a dhaba and I, these guys were there.

00:38:27.840 --> 00:38:34.920
[Guest]: So I saw that entourage and I, I just liked that image, the visual image it conjured up

00:38:34.920 --> 00:38:42.080
[Guest]: of people in white kurtas and topis and all those chirpais just outside the dhaba and,

00:38:42.080 --> 00:38:47.360
[Guest]: you know, some guys coming, people coming, touching the feet of this candidate. And so

00:38:47.360 --> 00:38:54.880
[Guest]: I, we had stopped at the dhaba for tea and I was watching these things happening there.

00:38:54.880 --> 00:39:02.080
[Guest]: And it was so fascinating for me that I wrote that scene. And when I came back to college,

00:39:02.080 --> 00:39:07.160
[Guest]: I was, we were sitting with some friends and I showed it to one of them. And then somehow

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:13.160
[Guest]: it went to my class teacher's hands. I don't know how that went there. And he was so fascinated.

00:39:13.160 --> 00:39:18.280
[Guest]: He asked me to come and read it out. So I was made to read it out to the class. And

00:39:18.280 --> 00:39:21.680
[Guest]: I was embarrassed because while I was reading, I realized that there were a lot of mistakes

00:39:21.680 --> 00:39:27.320
[Guest]: in it. The articles were missing in some places because I had just written it because it was

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:33.560
[Guest]: fascinating. So he told me that, you know, you have a very descriptive way of writing

00:39:33.560 --> 00:39:40.480
[Guest]: in this thing. Maybe you should pursue this a little more seriously. And I realized that

00:39:40.480 --> 00:39:47.440
[Guest]: even though I was probably not as proficient with the grammar of the language, I was able

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:54.960
[Guest]: to express myself and maybe use it in a way to describe things and maybe describe them

00:39:54.960 --> 00:40:03.000
[Guest]: in a manner which gives you a sense of what I had seen. So probably the Urdu poetry played

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:07.800
[Guest]: a role in this because there is a form in Urdu poetry, which is a descriptive form,

00:40:07.800 --> 00:40:12.160
[Guest]: you know, beyond Urdu poetry has a lot of forms. I mean, the most popular are ghazals

00:40:12.160 --> 00:40:17.760
[Guest]: and rubais to some extent. But then there are other forms also. There are forms where

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:24.480
[Guest]: you are describing scenes. There are forms where you're exaggerating situations. So it

00:40:24.480 --> 00:40:31.600
[Guest]: has a variety of forms. So when I was learning the poetry from my teacher, he acquainted

00:40:31.600 --> 00:40:37.200
[Guest]: me with these forms. And I was fascinated that actually poetry is not enough. Within

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:47.240
[Guest]: the poetry also, you have distinguished one form from another. And probably that had some

00:40:47.240 --> 00:40:54.720
[Guest]: sort of impact on me, just describing a situation as it was. Why I'm going on about describing

00:40:54.720 --> 00:41:01.760
[Guest]: a part is that maybe when I became a journalist, when I joined my first job, it was, I mean,

00:41:01.760 --> 00:41:06.440
[Guest]: my seniors decided that I should get into feature writing because I was more suited

00:41:06.440 --> 00:41:11.680
[Guest]: for feature writing as opposed to daily news reporting, because news reporting doesn't

00:41:11.680 --> 00:41:19.080
[Guest]: give you the option of or the luxury of just going off tangent and spending so much of

00:41:19.080 --> 00:41:29.440
[Guest]: space on building up the situation or building up the story. So I don't think I had a struggle

00:41:29.440 --> 00:41:37.200
[Guest]: as far as writing was concerned. The struggle part was always trying to cut short my flight

00:41:37.200 --> 00:41:38.960
[Guest]: of fancy and come to the point.

00:41:38.960 --> 00:41:43.040
[Amit Varma]: That's really fascinating. And, you know, someday we should do an episode on the different

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:48.640
[Amit Varma]: forms of writing in Urdu and all of that. But I suspect if I, although this is one of

00:41:48.640 --> 00:41:53.440
[Amit Varma]: my sort of pet themes, if I continue talking more with you about this, my listeners will

00:41:53.440 --> 00:41:57.520
[Amit Varma]: be that, hey, that's not the subject of the book, kindly get on with it. So, you know,

00:41:57.520 --> 00:42:02.440
[Amit Varma]: and it's interesting, you just spoke about how when you were in college in the late 80s,

00:42:02.440 --> 00:42:06.160
[Amit Varma]: when Mundell commission happened and your classmates approach and all and in the book,

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:12.540
[Amit Varma]: you also said something very interesting there, which is that none of them asked you anything

00:42:12.540 --> 00:42:16.900
[Amit Varma]: about yourself that even if they had their anti Muslim prejudices and all of that as

00:42:16.900 --> 00:42:22.520
[Amit Varma]: evident in their politics, you know, you almost wish that they would ask you what are Muslims

00:42:22.520 --> 00:42:26.240
[Amit Varma]: like, what is it like to be a Muslim and they never asked you, which was in contrast to

00:42:26.240 --> 00:42:32.240
[Amit Varma]: something which, you know, you described from your school days, when you write, quote, their

00:42:32.240 --> 00:42:37.280
[Amit Varma]: questions covered the entire gamut from genuine curiosity to inherited prejudice. Why do you

00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:42.480
[Amit Varma]: fast during Ramzan? Do you put meat in all your food? Some questions stemmed from stereotyping.

00:42:42.480 --> 00:42:46.480
[Amit Varma]: Why don't Muslims bathe every day? And some were downright ridiculous. How many mothers

00:42:46.480 --> 00:42:53.200
[Amit Varma]: do you have? Stop quote. And so my question to you is that, you know, on the one hand,

00:42:53.200 --> 00:42:58.400
[Amit Varma]: you are growing up in a Muslim family in a Muslim Mahalla. At the same time, your family

00:42:58.400 --> 00:43:03.360
[Amit Varma]: is kind of insulated itself from the street around it, like you describe how, you know,

00:43:03.360 --> 00:43:07.000
[Amit Varma]: all the rooms would have a window open to the inner courtyard, but none to the outside

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:11.000
[Amit Varma]: because you know, like you mentioned earlier, you weren't supposed to venture out, it wasn't

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:18.520
[Amit Varma]: safe, it wasn't great. So what was your personal view of Islam as a kid growing up? How big

00:43:18.520 --> 00:43:23.520
[Amit Varma]: a role did it play in your life? And how did you imbibe it? What did it mean to you? And

00:43:23.520 --> 00:43:28.320
[Amit Varma]: what did it mean to the other kids around you, like your cousins and so on?

00:43:28.320 --> 00:43:33.240
[Guest]: You know, when we were growing up, we were initiated into religion in a very simplistic

00:43:33.240 --> 00:43:39.960
[Guest]: manner. As kids, we were taught the first Kalma, which is just two lines. And that was

00:43:39.960 --> 00:43:45.520
[Guest]: enough. Beyond that, there was no formal initiation in terms of learning how to say the namaz

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:49.960
[Guest]: or learning to read the Quran, which is what happens in most Muslim households. You start

00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:56.080
[Guest]: learning the alphabets from a very young age. And in a conservative Muslim family, a child

00:43:56.080 --> 00:44:02.480
[Guest]: is expected to finish the entire reading of the Quran by the time she is seven years old.

00:44:02.480 --> 00:44:08.160
[Guest]: But in my family, that never happened. Not just my immediate siblings, but my cousins

00:44:08.160 --> 00:44:16.120
[Guest]: also, we never did that. Though we had a mosque right next to our house. And I grew up listening

00:44:16.120 --> 00:44:21.200
[Guest]: to the Muslims call from childhood. So much so because I used to hear it five times a

00:44:21.200 --> 00:44:25.880
[Guest]: day and sometimes more than that, because on special occasions, there used to be late

00:44:25.880 --> 00:44:34.720
[Guest]: night prayers as well. And because of which I knew it by heart. And sometimes, as part

00:44:34.720 --> 00:44:39.480
[Guest]: of our playing, we used to do a little bit of play acting. So one of my cousins would

00:44:39.480 --> 00:44:46.400
[Guest]: pretend to be the Hafiz who would give the call to prayer. So he would recite the prayer

00:44:46.400 --> 00:44:53.960
[Guest]: and we would join in. So it was all in good fun. Why we were not initiated into religion?

00:44:53.960 --> 00:44:59.680
[Guest]: Probably because my grandfather himself had a very laid back attitude to Islam. Though

00:44:59.680 --> 00:45:04.280
[Guest]: he was very diligent with his prayers and used to go to the mosque whenever he could.

00:45:04.280 --> 00:45:10.640
[Guest]: He never forced any of his children to do that. So his children didn't force their kids

00:45:10.640 --> 00:45:15.520
[Guest]: to do anything. It was left in a very laid back, easy manner that you recite the Kalma

00:45:15.520 --> 00:45:18.960
[Guest]: whenever you're worried or you're scared or before going to bed, just recite the Kalma

00:45:18.960 --> 00:45:25.040
[Guest]: and go to bed. That is a habit I have even today. I recite the Kalma before I go to bed.

00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:31.960
[Guest]: But that is how we were introduced to religion. It was only years later when we had moved

00:45:31.960 --> 00:45:39.280
[Guest]: to our new house and we were moving in a different direction from my cousins, that my uncles

00:45:39.280 --> 00:45:45.440
[Guest]: who were in the mohalla, maybe because there was no adult supervision. I mean, they themselves

00:45:45.440 --> 00:45:52.880
[Guest]: were adults with kids, but maybe because there was no umbrella of moderation, which my grandfather

00:45:52.880 --> 00:46:00.560
[Guest]: had provided to the family. And then my father, they kind of drifted first into the neighborhood.

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:05.000
[Guest]: They made friends in the neighborhood. Then the children, their kids, my younger cousins,

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:12.280
[Guest]: they started playing with the neighborhood kids. And then a religious teacher, Hafiz

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:18.920
[Guest]: was asked to teach my cousins. The reason he was asked was also because Hafiz had started

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:24.200
[Guest]: to come to our house because my grandfather's illness and it was thought that his presence

00:46:24.200 --> 00:46:32.480
[Guest]: would calm my grandfather and would make his day a little less boring. But despite the

00:46:32.480 --> 00:46:39.400
[Guest]: presence of a religious teacher in our house, my parents did not encourage us to learn anything

00:46:39.400 --> 00:46:47.840
[Guest]: from him. But my cousins started doing that. So that difference in this approach to religion,

00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:54.720
[Guest]: I think also had a little to do with the time that we were living in. By the late 80s, a

00:46:54.720 --> 00:47:03.680
[Guest]: lot of social situations had started to become a little bit shaded. There was a little consciousness

00:47:03.680 --> 00:47:11.200
[Guest]: about who you were. The Ram Mandir campaign had started. 84 onwards, there was this Babri

00:47:11.200 --> 00:47:18.360
[Guest]: issue had suddenly become a big issue in U.P. The newspapers used to be full of that. Hindi

00:47:18.360 --> 00:47:25.760
[Guest]: newspapers would be full of stuff like appeasement of minorities, as they would say, alp sankhekon

00:47:25.760 --> 00:47:32.480
[Guest]: ka tushrikaran. So people were becoming a little conscious of their identities. And

00:47:32.480 --> 00:47:40.840
[Guest]: maybe this initiation into religion was also a kind of a defiance that this is who we are.

00:47:40.840 --> 00:47:48.480
[Guest]: So I think that is why my, okay, there's another thing which I feel, because like my father,

00:47:48.480 --> 00:47:54.580
[Guest]: my uncles were also semi-literate. So my father worked on himself and he studied the languages

00:47:54.580 --> 00:48:00.000
[Guest]: and his aspirations were different from his brother's. My uncles didn't do that. So they

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:07.400
[Guest]: remained in their semi-literate Hindi-dominated world, Indian-dominated world. And as I mentioned

00:48:07.400 --> 00:48:14.680
[Guest]: earlier, the exposure to our world at that time was through the Hindi newspapers and

00:48:14.680 --> 00:48:22.800
[Guest]: the Urdu newspapers, and they both had nuance towards identity. So while the Hindi newspapers

00:48:22.800 --> 00:48:28.200
[Guest]: were conscious of its readership, which is a Hindi readership, and they imagined that

00:48:28.200 --> 00:48:35.040
[Guest]: this readership would probably like a story or a bent which favoured the Hindu communal

00:48:35.040 --> 00:48:43.200
[Guest]: sentiment, the Urdu newspapers were at the same time working on the Muslim sentiments.

00:48:43.200 --> 00:48:50.920
[Guest]: So their exposure was getting increasingly sharpened through this sort of writing. Probably

00:48:50.920 --> 00:48:56.480
[Guest]: that was another reason why they, and then subsequently my younger cousins, were drifting

00:48:56.480 --> 00:49:03.560
[Guest]: more and more into a Muslim milieu. The friends they chose also were traditionally Muslims.

00:49:03.560 --> 00:49:08.520
[Guest]: Though they went to the same schools as I went, I never had a Muslim friend in school.

00:49:08.520 --> 00:49:13.720
[Guest]: I mean one of the reasons was there was hardly any other Muslim child in my class. At least

00:49:13.720 --> 00:49:18.520
[Guest]: as long as I was in the convent, I was always the only Muslim girl in my class. Subsequently

00:49:18.520 --> 00:49:25.640
[Guest]: I moved to a co-educational institution, again a church-run institution. There was another

00:49:25.640 --> 00:49:31.160
[Guest]: Muslim in my class, but somehow I never got along with a Muslim and there was no desire

00:49:31.160 --> 00:49:38.080
[Guest]: that I should befriend a Muslim person. Similarly, that person also never felt that she should

00:49:38.080 --> 00:49:43.720
[Guest]: have a Muslim friend, so I had a different group of friends. But my younger cousins,

00:49:43.720 --> 00:49:50.300
[Guest]: I realised gradually that they used to veer towards Muslims more than any other community

00:49:50.300 --> 00:49:57.360
[Guest]: for the simple reason they felt comfortable with probably voicing their political positions,

00:49:57.360 --> 00:50:03.520
[Guest]: they felt secure in a Muslim environment. That was also one of the reasons that for

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:08.800
[Guest]: a very long time my uncles didn't shift out of the mohalla, though they had means to shift

00:50:08.800 --> 00:50:14.480
[Guest]: out. It's not that they were not doing well in their businesses, but they had grown comfortable

00:50:14.480 --> 00:50:20.920
[Guest]: in that. When I was growing up, we were not comfortable in that, which is why we had kept

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:26.640
[Guest]: our house isolated. It was almost like an island in that mohalla. But they had become

00:50:26.640 --> 00:50:31.400
[Guest]: comfortable. They had become comfortable going and visiting their neighbours' houses and

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:36.840
[Guest]: they were happy that neighbours were coming to their houses. So that was a difference.

00:50:36.840 --> 00:50:41.200
[Amit Varma]: So before I go on to my next question, a quick aside. You know, my favourite sentence in

00:50:41.200 --> 00:50:46.160
[Amit Varma]: your book is actually, you know, a great example of show-don't-tell and it's this lovely sentence

00:50:46.160 --> 00:50:51.840
[Amit Varma]: about your grandfather where you wrote, quote, during winter he used to shell pine nuts during

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:57.200
[Amit Varma]: the day so he could reward us with fistfuls of shelled nuts in the evening, stop quote.

00:50:57.200 --> 00:51:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's such a lovely sentence because it tells you so much about the person and his

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:05.400
[Amit Varma]: love for his grandkids and all of that. And I love that. Now, you know, it's interesting

00:51:05.400 --> 00:51:11.920
[Amit Varma]: that when I was sort of reading about the arc of your family, almost through the generations,

00:51:11.920 --> 00:51:17.380
[Amit Varma]: you talk about how initially, you know, your ancestors were, you know, in a settlement

00:51:17.380 --> 00:51:22.640
[Amit Varma]: outside Agra. And then your grandfather married a Syed, as you said, and, you know, wanted

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:27.960
[Amit Varma]: to be upwardly mobile, moved to Agra for that reason. But even moving to Agra wasn't the

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:32.520
[Amit Varma]: mobility alone, the mobility had to continue. So even though they had to move into a mahalla,

00:51:32.520 --> 00:51:38.120
[Amit Varma]: they've kind of kept themselves apart from everything outside. In fact, you know, you

00:51:38.120 --> 00:51:43.600
[Amit Varma]: describe how that lane outside was described to you as, quote, riddled with poverty, illiteracy,

00:51:43.600 --> 00:51:48.020
[Amit Varma]: backwardness and unthinkable danger, stop quote, which strikes me how many Hindus would

00:51:48.020 --> 00:51:53.520
[Amit Varma]: describe Muslim areas, even today. And then that further mobility happens where your nuclear

00:51:53.520 --> 00:51:58.520
[Amit Varma]: family and a younger uncle, you move to a separate place. And here, what is sort of

00:51:58.520 --> 00:52:04.440
[Amit Varma]: interesting to me is that you've gotten away from this sort of milieu, you've become mobile,

00:52:04.440 --> 00:52:09.560
[Amit Varma]: your dad has become very successful and rich. And you've moved, you know, almost out of

00:52:09.560 --> 00:52:14.640
[Amit Varma]: the ghetto, as it were. And, you know, you're living your individual lives. And at the same

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:19.440
[Amit Varma]: time, you described how your other uncles with their families remain back and they kind

00:52:19.440 --> 00:52:24.520
[Amit Varma]: of got drawn more and more into fundamentalism, in a sense, they open the doors and the windows

00:52:24.520 --> 00:52:30.280
[Amit Varma]: and let the lane inside in a metaphorical sense, I suppose, and that sort of journey

00:52:30.280 --> 00:52:36.760
[Amit Varma]: is happening. And they also then become more into the religion in terms of those other

00:52:36.760 --> 00:52:40.800
[Amit Varma]: sort of aspects of it, like you describe how for you, what Islam meant, as you've said,

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:44.560
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned how it came to you by driblets, which I found a, you know, wonderful phrase

00:52:44.560 --> 00:52:48.880
[Amit Varma]: in this regard. And you've mentioned how those sort of values you imbibe with the values

00:52:48.880 --> 00:52:53.080
[Amit Varma]: of charity that you know, during the holy month, you do charity, you feed the poor,

00:52:53.080 --> 00:52:58.440
[Amit Varma]: all of those things. But your cousins are taking in a sort of more fundamental version.

00:52:58.440 --> 00:53:03.760
[Amit Varma]: And what is sort of starkest about this distinction was that when you are 16, your father is giving

00:53:03.760 --> 00:53:08.000
[Amit Varma]: you prospectuses of universities abroad, because he wants you to go outside. And you describe

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:11.720
[Amit Varma]: how when you are writing an admission essay for one of them, one of your cousins in the

00:53:11.720 --> 00:53:17.280
[Amit Varma]: mahala is being felicitated for memorizing the entire Quran. And the reason this all

00:53:17.280 --> 00:53:23.840
[Amit Varma]: of this seemed fascinating to me is that the denouement that this comes to is an incident

00:53:23.840 --> 00:53:30.600
[Amit Varma]: where your father realizes that all this still doesn't insulate him from being a Muslim,

00:53:30.600 --> 00:53:35.360
[Amit Varma]: that in India, there is, you know, there are still things which can sort of go wrong and

00:53:35.360 --> 00:53:39.760
[Amit Varma]: all the riches in the world can't save you, you know, and this, of course, you've described

00:53:39.760 --> 00:53:44.160
[Amit Varma]: so eloquently in your book about how your house was attacked during a riot, and you

00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:48.080
[Amit Varma]: dialed all the numbers. And, you know, your father told you gave you all the numbers said

00:53:48.080 --> 00:53:52.640
[Amit Varma]: dial all these numbers, people were outside with stones, and all of your father's, you

00:53:52.640 --> 00:53:56.960
[Amit Varma]: know, friends did not pick up the phone at that time did not help. Tell me a little bit

00:53:56.960 --> 00:54:01.960
[Amit Varma]: about that and sort of the realization that comes out of that because this is like a deeply

00:54:01.960 --> 00:54:06.620
[Amit Varma]: poignant story. This is about, you know, different arcs, you know, you have the people who stayed

00:54:06.620 --> 00:54:11.280
[Amit Varma]: back in the mahala, you have the person who's escaped and who thinks that okay, he's beyond

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:18.280
[Amit Varma]: all of this. And yet, all of you are in a sense equally in danger in this India that

00:54:18.280 --> 00:54:23.040
[Amit Varma]: we are in. So tell me a little bit which year was this what was happening and all of that,

00:54:23.040 --> 00:54:28.640
[Guest]: you know, we, I never thought of myself as a Muslim while I was growing up, even when

00:54:28.640 --> 00:54:35.240
[Guest]: we lived in the mahala. So when I described the lanes, or when I have described the mahala,

00:54:35.240 --> 00:54:40.680
[Guest]: it was not something that I was condemning my own. Even at that time, when we were growing

00:54:40.680 --> 00:54:45.920
[Guest]: up, my family always thought that, why do they live like this? What is wrong with them?

00:54:45.920 --> 00:54:54.720
[Guest]: Why are the lanes kept so dirty? So we, they wanted to insulate us from what they viewed

00:54:54.720 --> 00:55:01.760
[Guest]: was people of a certain kind, not necessarily Muslims, though they were Muslims, all right,

00:55:01.760 --> 00:55:07.840
[Guest]: but we did not see ourselves as Muslims and we did not see them as Muslims. We just always

00:55:07.840 --> 00:55:14.880
[Guest]: thought that these people are less civil than we are and they have less ambitions and less

00:55:14.880 --> 00:55:25.960
[Guest]: desire to go beyond what they have inherited from their forefathers. So when we moved to

00:55:25.960 --> 00:55:32.200
[Guest]: this new area, which in India areas like this are called colonies, so we moved to this Hindu

00:55:32.200 --> 00:55:40.040
[Guest]: colony, we did not think at that point that we were the only Muslim in a Hindu colony.

00:55:40.040 --> 00:55:47.560
[Guest]: We were not conscious of our Muslimness and to our neighbor's credit, they also never

00:55:47.560 --> 00:55:53.280
[Guest]: made us conscious of our Muslimness. We got along fabulously with them and my parents

00:55:53.280 --> 00:55:57.880
[Guest]: were socializing with them. They were used to come to our house and there was a lot of

00:55:57.880 --> 00:56:05.080
[Guest]: intermingling in addition to special occasions. It's not that we met each other only on special

00:56:05.080 --> 00:56:09.200
[Guest]: occasions. There was a daily sort of a thing. My brother used to go out to play because

00:56:09.200 --> 00:56:14.360
[Guest]: now it was not a mohalla, so we were allowed to go out and play. And all the playmates

00:56:14.360 --> 00:56:20.640
[Guest]: were the neighborhood boys. So we were never conscious of the fact that we were different

00:56:20.640 --> 00:56:29.120
[Guest]: from the rest of them. A small example, so much so that a lot of neighborhood youngsters

00:56:29.120 --> 00:56:35.840
[Guest]: were older, much older than me, but roughly my younger uncle's age. They used to socialize

00:56:35.840 --> 00:56:41.320
[Guest]: with him also because my uncle had a car so they could hitch a ride and go for a night

00:56:41.320 --> 00:56:50.000
[Guest]: out. So that was, it was never considered that we were not part of this new society

00:56:50.000 --> 00:57:01.800
[Guest]: that we had embraced. When the 80s progressed and this atmospherics had changed so drastically,

00:57:01.800 --> 00:57:08.080
[Guest]: it was the first time that I actually became conscious that people were talking of Hindu

00:57:08.080 --> 00:57:21.240
[Guest]: and Muslim and in such harsh terms. My mother was into a lot of social work. My father was

00:57:21.240 --> 00:57:28.800
[Guest]: a big philanthropist. So she used to go to a lot of public functions and events. I remember

00:57:28.800 --> 00:57:37.320
[Guest]: sometimes in 88 or 89 probably, I don't know the year exactly, there was a big police function

00:57:37.320 --> 00:57:43.960
[Guest]: in Agra. And my mother was invited to that function as one of the delegates or some attendee.

00:57:43.960 --> 00:57:51.000
[Guest]: But my mother used to work with the Agra district jail people and she was doing some work in

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:57.640
[Guest]: adult literacy with the women, the families of the jail inmates. Because at district jail

00:57:57.640 --> 00:58:03.640
[Guest]: people, most people who were there, the prisoners, they were there serving life sentences. So

00:58:03.640 --> 00:58:10.040
[Guest]: the jail had built a small enclosure there for the families and kids to live. So my mother

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:16.760
[Guest]: used to, with a group of people, she was working in that area. So she was invited to this event,

00:58:16.760 --> 00:58:23.440
[Guest]: police, Agra police event, and I tagged along with her because I had nothing better to do.

00:58:23.440 --> 00:58:32.600
[Guest]: And BP Singhal, who was the brother of Ashok Singhal, he retired as a DG police UP. He

00:58:32.600 --> 00:58:38.880
[Guest]: was one of the speakers at the function. And the kind of language he used at that event

00:58:38.880 --> 00:58:46.040
[Guest]: and the way he spoke, it was beyond shocking. I could not believe that in a public event

00:58:46.040 --> 00:58:51.800
[Guest]: where all kinds of people are present, somebody could speak like this and not feel embarrassed,

00:58:51.800 --> 00:58:56.600
[Guest]: not feel concerned that some people may get hurt or they may feel bad the way you're talking

00:58:56.600 --> 00:59:03.280
[Guest]: about them. And the fact that we are sitting there, it didn't occur to him that he should

00:59:03.280 --> 00:59:10.120
[Guest]: not be talking like this. And then there was stray slogan shouting. So every time somebody

00:59:10.120 --> 00:59:15.080
[Guest]: would shout a slogan or say something, I would turn back and see who's saying this. But obviously

00:59:15.080 --> 00:59:22.200
[Guest]: you can't see it. It's a huge crowd. So that was very disturbing. I had not imagined something

00:59:22.200 --> 00:59:26.760
[Guest]: like this could happen in a public space. I thought probably if even people feel like

00:59:26.760 --> 00:59:31.960
[Guest]: that, they would talk about this inside their homes and be mindful that nobody else hears

00:59:31.960 --> 00:59:37.720
[Guest]: this. Even in my own family, extended family, I used to hear things like, you know, there

00:59:37.720 --> 00:59:45.160
[Guest]: is all of us are prejudiced. We kind of inherit our prejudices. So we would talk. I mean,

00:59:45.160 --> 00:59:51.000
[Guest]: my family members would often talk about Hindus or Christians or Sikhs in a particular manner,

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:56.880
[Guest]: but it would always be inside the house and it was always among the close family members.

00:59:56.880 --> 01:00:03.560
[Guest]: It was not meant for public consumption. But here this was being said loud and clear in

01:00:03.560 --> 01:00:13.160
[Guest]: an event where all kinds of people were present. So I realized that things were really not

01:00:13.160 --> 01:00:21.720
[Guest]: right. Things were going bad. And then these audio cassettes came of Advani and Sadhvi

01:00:21.720 --> 01:00:28.560
[Guest]: Ritambara and their speeches. They were being distributed. One of my father's closest friends,

01:00:28.560 --> 01:00:34.240
[Guest]: all my father's friends were also Hindus. So he started distributing the cassettes and

01:00:34.240 --> 01:00:39.920
[Guest]: then he would have discussions with my father, which again is a measure of how comfortable

01:00:39.920 --> 01:00:44.160
[Guest]: he was with my father and how comfortable my father was with him. And he would discuss

01:00:44.160 --> 01:00:50.360
[Guest]: the content of the speeches. He would talk about barbary, he would talk about destruction

01:00:50.360 --> 01:00:54.960
[Guest]: of temples. And my father would say, no, no, it's all nonsense. And they both would have

01:00:54.960 --> 01:01:00.480
[Guest]: these arguments, but they would have these arguments that Somnath was destroyed so many

01:01:00.480 --> 01:01:05.200
[Guest]: times. And so my father would reason out that, look, it was political. And maybe how would

01:01:05.200 --> 01:01:10.520
[Guest]: he know every time that the temple was flushed with funds? If he was coming at the time when

01:01:10.520 --> 01:01:14.320
[Guest]: the temple was flushed, then somebody was informing him. That is how he was coming all

01:01:14.320 --> 01:01:23.360
[Guest]: the way from Afghanistan. But the good part was that though their paths were diverging

01:01:23.360 --> 01:01:30.480
[Guest]: a little, politically they were getting distant, they still had this history of friendship

01:01:30.480 --> 01:01:36.480
[Guest]: between them. So they could talk. But when I came to Delhi, nobody spoke to me about

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:40.920
[Guest]: this. Nobody asked me any question, which is what disturbed me the most, that if you

01:01:40.920 --> 01:01:48.040
[Guest]: have any questions about Muslims, if you think that Muslims as people are different in a

01:01:48.040 --> 01:01:52.480
[Guest]: particular way because this is what they've done wrong, then if you ask me, maybe I can

01:01:52.480 --> 01:01:59.240
[Guest]: find out the answer for you if I don't know. But that did not happen. So going back to

01:01:59.240 --> 01:02:06.640
[Guest]: the attack, the 1990, I was already in college and I had already seen what was happening

01:02:06.640 --> 01:02:13.040
[Guest]: in Delhi and my classmates. And all of them were voting BJP. All of us were first-time

01:02:13.040 --> 01:02:19.560
[Guest]: voters and they said, no, no, how can we vote for anybody else? We vote for the BJP. And

01:02:19.560 --> 01:02:27.000
[Guest]: whatever people may say or justify, the truth is the history of the BJP origin song is it

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:35.080
[Guest]: stems from otherization of certain group of people in India. They've always done politics

01:02:35.080 --> 01:02:43.760
[Guest]: which pits community against community. So nobody can whitewash this part about the BJP.

01:02:43.760 --> 01:02:48.520
[Guest]: So despite this, if some people are convinced that they only want to vote for that party,

01:02:48.520 --> 01:02:54.000
[Guest]: it means that you at some level agree with them or you at some level believe that what

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:59.160
[Guest]: they're saying is correct. So it was this sort of a background that I was called back

01:02:59.160 --> 01:03:06.320
[Guest]: home and our neighbors were coming and warning my parents that something is going to happen.

01:03:06.320 --> 01:03:13.040
[Guest]: You go back to your house in the mahala. Violence had broken out in Agra in certain areas. One

01:03:13.040 --> 01:03:20.240
[Guest]: of my uncle's friends, his shop, he had a shoe shop that was burned. So we all were

01:03:20.240 --> 01:03:30.040
[Guest]: quite anxious. Finally, my father said, okay, we didn't want to go back to the mahala. Because

01:03:30.040 --> 01:03:35.440
[Guest]: once you leave, in any case, it was a small house. And once we left, the rooms that we

01:03:35.440 --> 01:03:43.160
[Guest]: had was now occupied by my cousins and my other uncle's family. So then my father booked

01:03:43.160 --> 01:03:51.320
[Guest]: us in Mughal Sheraton and my mother drove us to the hotel. Then sometimes in the late

01:03:51.320 --> 01:03:58.640
[Guest]: afternoon, she got very anxious. And this was the day when our neighbors had persistently

01:03:58.640 --> 01:04:05.080
[Guest]: pushed my father that, you know, we have information and there's nothing we can do. And my father

01:04:05.080 --> 01:04:09.840
[Guest]: saw their point. You know, you can't argue with a mob and you don't know what the mob

01:04:09.840 --> 01:04:18.800
[Guest]: would do or what the size of the mob would be. And it doesn't really make sense that

01:04:18.800 --> 01:04:25.720
[Guest]: you expect your neighbors to stick their necks out. They could probably, but why take a chance?

01:04:25.720 --> 01:04:31.840
[Guest]: So my father sent us off, but we came back in the afternoon because my mother was very,

01:04:31.840 --> 01:04:39.280
[Guest]: very anxious. And sure enough, in the evening, there was a lot of slogan shouting happening.

01:04:39.280 --> 01:04:45.000
[Guest]: So my father gave me this telephone book and he said, just call up these people, keep calling

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:50.680
[Guest]: them up and tell them that our house is likely to be under attack. And these are the people

01:04:50.680 --> 01:04:57.840
[Guest]: my father had been socializing with for many years. You know, in a small town, whenever

01:04:57.840 --> 01:05:04.760
[Guest]: there is a new DM or a new DIG, it's customary. I mean, they also come and they ask their

01:05:04.760 --> 01:05:10.000
[Guest]: office staff that who are the people that we should know. And the business families,

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:15.680
[Guest]: they also feel that it's a matter of prestige that you're friends with the district authorities.

01:05:15.680 --> 01:05:21.720
[Guest]: So apart from the prestige part, it's also some sort of insurance cover that if you need,

01:05:21.720 --> 01:05:28.440
[Guest]: you can ask these guys to help you. So we knew most of the district authorities very,

01:05:28.440 --> 01:05:37.800
[Guest]: very well. But that evening, nobody answered any calls, even though I called up the residences

01:05:37.800 --> 01:05:48.840
[Guest]: also, but nobody answered any calls. And around dusk when it had just about to get a bit dark,

01:05:48.840 --> 01:05:59.360
[Guest]: a mob started walking towards our house. And our house is, we have a very narrow, a short

01:05:59.360 --> 01:06:06.000
[Guest]: porch and then there's a gate. And the inside door has a glass panel on one side. So from

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:12.600
[Guest]: the glass panel, you can see the porch and the gate and the road beyond. So my brother,

01:06:12.600 --> 01:06:17.440
[Guest]: younger brother and I, we ran to the glass panel and we started looking out and we saw

01:06:17.440 --> 01:06:24.480
[Guest]: this big group of people carrying fire torches walking towards our house. And my mother was

01:06:24.480 --> 01:06:29.840
[Guest]: screaming, she said, come back in, come back in, because she thought we may get hurt. And

01:06:29.840 --> 01:06:35.880
[Guest]: they came and stopped in front of the gate and they were shouting slogans. And then we

01:06:35.880 --> 01:06:42.440
[Guest]: identified this neighborhood boy and we came back, we ran inside and said, oh, this boy

01:06:42.440 --> 01:06:48.400
[Guest]: is there. So my father was very sanguine. He said, oh, so obviously they won't do anything

01:06:48.400 --> 01:06:55.240
[Guest]: because this boy, he knows us so well. But then they started throwing stones and that

01:06:55.240 --> 01:07:02.600
[Guest]: is when everybody panicked because the distance between the gate and the house is not much.

01:07:02.600 --> 01:07:08.520
[Guest]: And my father had a licensed revolver. So my uncle knew where it was kept. He went in

01:07:08.520 --> 01:07:14.200
[Guest]: my father's room, he took it out and he tried to go to the rooftop and he said, I'll just

01:07:14.200 --> 01:07:19.520
[Guest]: fire a few shots in the air. And my father had better sense. He shouted and screamed

01:07:19.520 --> 01:07:25.720
[Guest]: after him and my mother also kind of ran after him to pull him back physically. Father said

01:07:25.720 --> 01:07:32.160
[Guest]: that if you fire one shot, they'll burn the house down. Finally, my uncle calmed down

01:07:32.160 --> 01:07:39.040
[Guest]: and he came back. And after a bit of stone pelting and they destroyed the car which was

01:07:39.040 --> 01:07:46.000
[Guest]: parked outside, the windscreen, everything was shattered. Our glass windows were, even

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:51.200
[Guest]: the first floor window, the study which used to face the main road and which used to be

01:07:51.200 --> 01:07:57.680
[Guest]: my favorite place to sit and look at the road and the traffic. It was very badly damaged.

01:07:57.680 --> 01:08:05.120
[Guest]: The windows were crashed, the stones had landed inside the study, the sitting area. We had

01:08:05.120 --> 01:08:13.440
[Guest]: huge glass windows. So they had kind of broken everything. So finally, after a bit of stone

01:08:13.440 --> 01:08:20.880
[Guest]: throwing, I think it must have lasted about 10-15 minutes, the crowd dispersed. And then

01:08:20.880 --> 01:08:27.280
[Guest]: at that point, my call got through and somebody answered from the SSP's house. And they said,

01:08:27.280 --> 01:08:32.840
[Guest]: the SSP didn't come on the line. Probably he was busy because there were riots going

01:08:32.840 --> 01:08:37.920
[Guest]: on all over the city. So somebody answered the call and they said, we'll send a patrol

01:08:37.920 --> 01:08:44.800
[Guest]: party to your house, which came very late in the night, well past 10.30 or so. So my

01:08:44.800 --> 01:08:49.040
[Guest]: uncle and my father went to speak with the policemen and they said, no, no, we'll include

01:08:49.040 --> 01:08:54.680
[Guest]: your house in our nightly rounds, so nothing will happen. Don't worry, go to sleep. Obviously,

01:08:54.680 --> 01:09:04.520
[Guest]: we couldn't have slept with so much of fear all around. And then next morning, there was

01:09:04.520 --> 01:09:12.920
[Guest]: a police cordon and search operation was carried out in that mahalla where my uncles were.

01:09:12.920 --> 01:09:20.720
[Guest]: And all men, and they didn't distinguish between men and boys, they were rounded up and taken

01:09:20.720 --> 01:09:28.280
[Guest]: away. So my cousin, who's six years younger than me, he was also picked up. He must have

01:09:28.280 --> 01:09:39.120
[Guest]: been 13 or something. And fortunately, there was an elderly constable who took pity on

01:09:39.120 --> 01:09:46.840
[Guest]: him or he probably recognized him from belonging to this family. So he allowed him to jump

01:09:46.840 --> 01:09:51.520
[Guest]: from the jeep when it was turning on the main road. And from there, he walked to our house

01:09:51.520 --> 01:09:59.480
[Guest]: and informed us that this is what has happened. So my uncle and my mother and I, we, because

01:09:59.480 --> 01:10:06.160
[Guest]: by this time I was studying to be a journalist and I had assumed the role of a reporter already.

01:10:06.160 --> 01:10:15.080
[Guest]: So I tagged along and we went to the house and it was absolutely quiet. There was no

01:10:15.080 --> 01:10:21.200
[Guest]: noise at all. And this was a house which was always so noisy. People were screaming on

01:10:21.200 --> 01:10:27.200
[Guest]: top of their voices. There was no privacy for anything. And it was absolutely eerie.

01:10:27.200 --> 01:10:34.440
[Guest]: There was no noise, no sound. So we opened the door, my mother pushed the door and it

01:10:34.440 --> 01:10:40.120
[Guest]: opened into that central courtyard. And there were things strewn all over. There was a television

01:10:40.120 --> 01:10:47.000
[Guest]: set, there was a cricket bat, there was a lot of things lying there. And my mother obviously

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:55.920
[Guest]: in total panic, she screamed my auntie's name. And they were all huddling in one of the storerooms,

01:10:55.920 --> 01:11:05.720
[Guest]: in the ground floor room. So they came running out and everybody was crying. And then they

01:11:05.720 --> 01:11:12.360
[Guest]: narrated how the police had come early in the morning and taken everybody away. My father

01:11:12.360 --> 01:11:21.520
[Guest]: and my uncle, they went round to various places. My father went to the DIG's office, but my

01:11:21.520 --> 01:11:25.880
[Guest]: uncle went to another, the local police station and they kept denying that anything like this

01:11:25.880 --> 01:11:33.120
[Guest]: had happened. But finally, my father managed to speak with the DIG and he said, nothing

01:11:33.120 --> 01:11:38.240
[Guest]: will happen. I assure you that your brothers will come back. They came back late in the

01:11:38.240 --> 01:11:47.360
[Guest]: afternoon and they were quite badly bruised. All the men from the neighbourhood, they came

01:11:47.360 --> 01:11:52.560
[Guest]: back in the course of the night and the next morning. They were even badly hurt. A few

01:11:52.560 --> 01:11:59.360
[Guest]: were hobbling and probably some had broken bones. Fortunately, my uncles didn't have

01:11:59.360 --> 01:12:04.120
[Guest]: any broken bones, but they were bruised. They were hit on their calves and on their backs

01:12:04.120 --> 01:12:12.640
[Guest]: by batons or something. So they had all those blue and black belts on their backs. And my

01:12:12.640 --> 01:12:22.400
[Guest]: younger uncle had a cut on his forehead, very close to the eyelid. So that was a very harrowing

01:12:22.400 --> 01:12:33.160
[Guest]: thing because all of us kind of got together and was wondering that you think that if you're

01:12:33.160 --> 01:12:42.160
[Guest]: living in a mixed community, you would be secure because it's upper middle class society

01:12:42.160 --> 01:12:50.560
[Guest]: or a colony where people of a certain class live. So it will be insulated from petty roadside

01:12:50.560 --> 01:12:57.040
[Guest]: violence, but that doesn't happen. And then you think that in a Muslim mohalla, everybody

01:12:57.040 --> 01:13:02.520
[Guest]: is a Muslim, so you have security in numbers. But then if the police gets after you, then

01:13:02.520 --> 01:13:08.400
[Guest]: even that is no longer secure. Probably a mohalla is secure from a riot because a mob,

01:13:08.400 --> 01:13:14.280
[Guest]: a Hindu mob will not enter a mohalla thing because of preponderance of Muslim population.

01:13:14.280 --> 01:13:20.640
[Guest]: But what do you do if the police enters? So basically, if you have to be targeted, if

01:13:20.640 --> 01:13:26.680
[Guest]: there is a political directive that a particular lesson has to be taught or a few hours notice,

01:13:26.680 --> 01:13:30.520
[Guest]: you know, it's a window of a few hours that you give, okay, just do whatever you want

01:13:30.520 --> 01:13:35.920
[Guest]: and then the law enforcement will take its course. So if that kind of a thing happens

01:13:35.920 --> 01:13:42.040
[Guest]: in a situation, then it doesn't matter what distance you have traveled, your education,

01:13:42.040 --> 01:13:51.800
[Guest]: your financial situation, your thinking, your world view, even your modernity or progressiveness,

01:13:51.800 --> 01:13:55.000
[Guest]: none of that matters at all.

01:13:55.000 --> 01:13:59.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I was struck by this trade-off which should not exist in the first place.

01:13:59.320 --> 01:14:04.240
[Amit Varma]: It should not be a trade-off. But it's a trade-off that comes up when your, you know, dad is

01:14:04.240 --> 01:14:09.320
[Amit Varma]: thinking of shifting your family from the mohalla and you write at that point, quote,

01:14:09.320 --> 01:14:13.400
[Amit Varma]: we didn't know where we would be more secure, in an upscale Hindu majority neighborhood

01:14:13.400 --> 01:14:17.160
[Amit Varma]: where the privilege of the residents would throw a security blanket around us, or in

01:14:17.160 --> 01:14:21.640
[Amit Varma]: a Muslim majority lower middle class mohalla where the numbers would insulate us, stop

01:14:21.640 --> 01:14:25.400
[Amit Varma]: quote, which sort of reminds me of something that, you know, when I was chatting with Annie

01:14:25.400 --> 01:14:30.120
[Amit Varma]: Zaidi in my last episode, you know, there's this poignant quote from her book about home

01:14:30.120 --> 01:14:35.100
[Amit Varma]: is not just a place where you are safe, it is a place where you can be visible. And that

01:14:35.100 --> 01:14:40.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of, you know, strikes me in this context. And later on, after, you know, the riot happened

01:14:40.880 --> 01:14:46.880
[Amit Varma]: and all of this happened, you wrote, quote, in the family comprising six brothers and

01:14:46.880 --> 01:14:52.240
[Amit Varma]: four sisters, these two men had most visibly shed their ghettoized Muslim identities. They

01:14:52.240 --> 01:14:56.840
[Amit Varma]: were at home in the social, cultural and economic life of Agra, hobnobbing with the who's who

01:14:56.840 --> 01:15:02.560
[Amit Varma]: of the city. And yet, when it came to communal division, they were nothing but Muslims, forever

01:15:02.560 --> 01:15:08.360
[Amit Varma]: immigrants, forever scapegoats, stop quote. And then you talk about how, as this period

01:15:08.360 --> 01:15:14.000
[Amit Varma]: progresses, and obviously Hindu nationalism is on the rise, Hindutva nationalism rather,

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:19.200
[Amit Varma]: and you talk about, you write, quote, demonstrative religion was all around us. As a benign Ram

01:15:19.200 --> 01:15:23.560
[Amit Varma]: Ram was replaced by the militant Jai Shri Ram, people started huddling with their own

01:15:23.560 --> 01:15:27.360
[Amit Varma]: kind. A lot of business class Muslims who had stepped out of the mohallas and built

01:15:27.360 --> 01:15:32.660
[Amit Varma]: swanky houses in mixed localities, returned to the smothering comforts of narrow lanes

01:15:32.660 --> 01:15:38.120
[Amit Varma]: and close minds, stop quote, which is of course, not just literal, but metaphorical. Tell me

01:15:38.120 --> 01:15:43.720
[Amit Varma]: about this kind of shift that now happens because it strikes me that this is going to

01:15:43.720 --> 01:15:49.160
[Amit Varma]: be the natural tendency that if I am attacked, if I am seen as another, I will obviously

01:15:49.160 --> 01:15:54.680
[Amit Varma]: look for comfort from, you know, those of my own kind. So it almost makes this ghettoization

01:15:54.680 --> 01:16:02.000
[Amit Varma]: completely natural. And obviously, you know, my sort of reading of, you know, the history

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:05.960
[Amit Varma]: of the last couple of hundred years, and we'll discuss that in much more detail because you've

01:16:05.960 --> 01:16:10.560
[Amit Varma]: written about that in your book as well. But my reading is that these fissures have always

01:16:10.560 --> 01:16:16.680
[Amit Varma]: kind of existed, but it's only now that in a sense politics has caught up with culture.

01:16:16.680 --> 01:16:23.000
[Amit Varma]: So is that what is happening? Is it a vicious circle? Is there this increased ghettoization,

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:27.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, what was your own response to this? And what was the response of others around

01:16:27.320 --> 01:16:28.320
[Amit Varma]: you?

01:16:28.320 --> 01:16:34.560
[Guest]: You know, there is, I would like to make a distinction between a Muslim majority area

01:16:34.560 --> 01:16:44.440
[Guest]: and a ghetto. Now, a lot of Indian towns, they have community specific areas, which

01:16:44.440 --> 01:16:48.920
[Guest]: have grown organically, which have developed organically in a city, like in Delhi, you

01:16:48.920 --> 01:16:56.640
[Guest]: have Dajama Masjid area, or you have Nizamuddin West area, which were always part of the city.

01:16:56.640 --> 01:17:02.840
[Guest]: Or in Bombay, you have Muhammad Ali Road, or you have Bindi Bazaar. So Muslims have

01:17:02.840 --> 01:17:07.800
[Guest]: traditionally lived here. They did not go there because they were scared of living anywhere

01:17:07.800 --> 01:17:14.280
[Guest]: else. They have lived there for generations, and even rich, prosperous Muslims live there.

01:17:14.280 --> 01:17:19.960
[Guest]: The facilities, which other areas in the neighborhood have, are probably available to these areas

01:17:19.960 --> 01:17:27.800
[Guest]: also. As an example, a ghetto would be a place like Mumbra, outside Bombay, which emerges

01:17:27.800 --> 01:17:35.840
[Guest]: after an incident of communal violence, because people move there for security reasons. A

01:17:35.840 --> 01:17:40.840
[Guest]: Muslim majority area, people live there not so much for security reasons, but because

01:17:40.840 --> 01:17:44.920
[Guest]: they have lived there, they're comfortable there. The kind of people, they've grown up

01:17:44.920 --> 01:17:54.400
[Guest]: there, live, are all around them. They identify themselves more as Muslims, so they're comfortable

01:17:54.400 --> 01:17:59.240
[Guest]: with Muslims around. Their eating habits are similar, their mosque is there, so they can

01:17:59.240 --> 01:18:06.000
[Guest]: go there. There's a madarsa there for the children. So it's a comfort factor. So most

01:18:06.000 --> 01:18:16.240
[Guest]: small towns in India have these Muslim areas. So the mahala which I grew up was dirty and

01:18:16.240 --> 01:18:21.920
[Guest]: all of that, but it was not a ghetto in the real sense of a ghetto as you find in Delhi

01:18:21.920 --> 01:18:32.560
[Guest]: now in the Okhla region. Because Okhla area is a ghetto, you find this huge presence of

01:18:32.560 --> 01:18:39.120
[Guest]: police there, and a policeman in plain clothes. They are basically spies, they are basically

01:18:39.120 --> 01:18:45.720
[Guest]: from the intelligence agencies, they're trying keeping tabs. This is the area where, if you

01:18:45.720 --> 01:18:53.280
[Guest]: have an address of Okhla or Batla House in Delhi, you are less likely to get a bank loan.

01:18:53.280 --> 01:18:58.760
[Guest]: You're not 100% not going to get a credit card. The delivery services, even a pizza

01:18:58.760 --> 01:19:03.280
[Guest]: delivery is not possible. The pizza delivery boy would say, okay, you come at some point

01:19:03.280 --> 01:19:09.320
[Guest]: and I'll leave the pizza there. So these are the places which are not organic to a city.

01:19:09.320 --> 01:19:15.260
[Guest]: These are the places that have developed because the law enforcement agencies have not acted

01:19:15.260 --> 01:19:23.640
[Guest]: on time and the government has not done anything to prevent this sort of pervasive fear from

01:19:23.640 --> 01:19:32.400
[Guest]: taking grip over the people. What happened in Agra, after this incident of 1990, that

01:19:32.400 --> 01:19:37.880
[Guest]: was the only Hindu-Muslim communal riot in Agra. Agra has no history of communal violence.

01:19:37.880 --> 01:19:43.720
[Guest]: Even during partition, there was no communal violence in Agra. So it has always been very

01:19:43.720 --> 01:19:48.520
[Guest]: insulated from communal prejudice. I mean, people may have been prejudiced, but it was

01:19:48.520 --> 01:19:53.680
[Guest]: never vocalized. But all this happened in the late 80s when it was being vocalized,

01:19:53.680 --> 01:20:02.080
[Guest]: early 90s, where people have started talking in this very criminally charged and harsh,

01:20:02.080 --> 01:20:10.720
[Guest]: impolite, uncivil language. So this, even today, Agra has a lot of places where Muslims

01:20:10.720 --> 01:20:17.720
[Guest]: live predominantly. And after the 1990 violence, a lot of Muslims who had moved to fancy swanky

01:20:17.720 --> 01:20:26.400
[Guest]: places like our family, they went back. A few of them, I have heard from my brothers

01:20:26.400 --> 01:20:30.080
[Guest]: that have returned to their houses because they didn't sell their houses. They just went

01:20:30.080 --> 01:20:38.160
[Guest]: back to the family homes. They have, by the mid-2000s, 2004, 2005, when they thought that

01:20:38.160 --> 01:20:46.160
[Guest]: things are getting a little better, they came back. And probably there is a political point

01:20:46.160 --> 01:20:51.360
[Guest]: here because you see the government, which were in power in this period, both in the

01:20:51.360 --> 01:21:00.480
[Guest]: UP and at the center. So maybe that gave them some sort of a confidence that we will not

01:21:00.480 --> 01:21:07.040
[Guest]: be subjected to violence. But all that changed again, 2014 onwards, when the fear of the

01:21:07.040 --> 01:21:17.480
[Guest]: 90s has been not just reinforced, it has multiplied manifold. Because even in the 90s, when there

01:21:17.480 --> 01:21:23.920
[Guest]: was violence, you feared for your life and you feared for your property for the duration

01:21:23.920 --> 01:21:29.680
[Guest]: of the violence. It was a riot which went on for two days or three days. You feared

01:21:29.680 --> 01:21:37.840
[Guest]: for that duration and then you rebuilt your life whichever way it was and you moved on.

01:21:37.840 --> 01:21:45.120
[Guest]: What is happening now is that the fear is not limited to the duration of a riot because

01:21:45.120 --> 01:21:53.540
[Guest]: now there is no riot. Now it is something which you are subjected to on a daily basis.

01:21:53.540 --> 01:21:58.240
[Guest]: So you hear people saying that in public transport, we don't greet each other with Salam-o-Alaikum

01:21:58.240 --> 01:22:04.400
[Guest]: because we don't want to draw attention to ourselves. Or people not carrying food from

01:22:04.400 --> 01:22:13.840
[Guest]: home. A very senior surgeon told me in the book that he is scared of bringing Eid food

01:22:13.840 --> 01:22:20.320
[Guest]: from his hometown when he comes to Delhi after Eid celebrations because he worries for his

01:22:20.320 --> 01:22:32.320
[Guest]: family. So this fear that even privilege is no insurance was not there earlier. One of

01:22:32.320 --> 01:22:37.560
[Guest]: the reasons that my family, my father thought that we will be safe because he felt confident

01:22:37.560 --> 01:22:43.000
[Guest]: that we are too privileged. I mean, if we can afford to go in a five-star hotel to stay,

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:49.760
[Guest]: then you can imagine in our mind, we believe that the poor are affected. It's not people

01:22:49.760 --> 01:23:02.000
[Guest]: like us will not be affected. But that doesn't happen any longer. This divisive violence

01:23:02.000 --> 01:23:12.800
[Guest]: is now indiscriminate. So when we talk about Muslims being caught between this lack of

01:23:12.800 --> 01:23:23.800
[Guest]: choice about where to live, it's partly because of this normalization of prejudice. We are

01:23:23.800 --> 01:23:31.800
[Guest]: not embarrassed by our prejudice anymore. We believe that what our prejudice tells us

01:23:31.800 --> 01:23:40.000
[Guest]: is actually the fact. We don't even pause to consider that maybe it's nonsense. Maybe

01:23:40.000 --> 01:23:48.840
[Guest]: it's just something which we've heard or it's hearsay. Because of this, you hear instances

01:23:48.840 --> 01:23:53.320
[Guest]: of Muslims not finding accommodation. But again, it's a big city phenomenon. I don't

01:23:53.320 --> 01:24:00.160
[Guest]: think in a small city like Agra, Muslims live everywhere. It's unthinkable. I've never come

01:24:00.160 --> 01:24:07.920
[Guest]: across anybody telling me that they were not able to find accommodation in a place which

01:24:07.920 --> 01:24:15.360
[Guest]: was predominantly non-Muslim. So this is a big city place where probably the size of

01:24:15.360 --> 01:24:21.040
[Guest]: the city, the insecurity which a big city instills in you, the economic challenges which

01:24:21.040 --> 01:24:32.960
[Guest]: it imposes upon you, maybe it is all driven by that. For want of anything else, you channel

01:24:32.960 --> 01:24:40.800
[Guest]: or you channelize your dislike for a certain group of people. So you deny them equal opportunities,

01:24:40.800 --> 01:24:48.280
[Guest]: you deny them accommodation, you deny them civility. So what is the choice then? Then

01:24:48.280 --> 01:24:58.520
[Guest]: they have to go and look for a place in a ghetto, even if they don't get along with

01:24:58.520 --> 01:25:05.760
[Guest]: that sort of Muslim population, even if they're forward-looking educated people. I'll give

01:25:05.760 --> 01:25:11.640
[Guest]: you an example. When I first came to Delhi as a student, I lived as a paying guest with

01:25:11.640 --> 01:25:18.400
[Guest]: a Muslim family for a year and then I moved into my own flat. My father rented a flat

01:25:18.400 --> 01:25:24.160
[Guest]: in South Extension. Now South Extension was in Delhi, is a South Delhi area. I don't know

01:25:24.160 --> 01:25:29.800
[Guest]: how familiar you are with the Delhi social hierarchy of places. So it's a reasonably

01:25:29.800 --> 01:25:36.600
[Guest]: fancy place and with hardly any Muslims there. I had no problem finding accommodation there

01:25:36.600 --> 01:25:43.360
[Guest]: and then I moved to another place. I lived in rented accommodation for nearly 11 years

01:25:43.360 --> 01:25:51.360
[Guest]: before we bought an apartment here. I never had any problem finding a rented accommodation

01:25:51.360 --> 01:25:57.440
[Guest]: and all my landlords were non-Muslims and nobody ever asked me to vacate the flat. I

01:25:57.440 --> 01:26:03.840
[Guest]: mean I moved for, because of my jobs, I moved from one place to another and I changed three

01:26:03.840 --> 01:26:10.140
[Guest]: apartments and in each I lived for nearly three to four years and I never had any problems.

01:26:10.140 --> 01:26:14.960
[Guest]: Nobody told me don't cook non-vegetarian food, nobody said anything. But when my cousins

01:26:14.960 --> 01:26:27.520
[Guest]: came in 2007 and they came from an even smaller town than Agra, they came from Menpuri and

01:26:27.520 --> 01:26:32.320
[Guest]: they couldn't find accommodation. Every time they would approach a broker, they were told

01:26:32.320 --> 01:26:41.320
[Guest]: go to Batla House, go to Okla. They did manage to live in East Delhi but with great difficulty.

01:26:41.320 --> 01:26:46.760
[Guest]: Finding accommodation for them was always a huge struggle and even if they did find

01:26:46.760 --> 01:26:51.080
[Guest]: accommodation within a year or so, the landlord or the landlady used to pester them to vacate

01:26:51.080 --> 01:26:55.560
[Guest]: the place because things have changed so much.

01:26:55.560 --> 01:27:00.520
[Amit Varma]: That's a very subtle distinction that you drew between a ghetto and a Muslim majority

01:27:00.520 --> 01:27:06.920
[Amit Varma]: area. I mean I was just using it in a general kind of sense but I find that that distinction

01:27:06.920 --> 01:27:15.120
[Amit Varma]: that you made is important because it also tells you a little bit about why it has kind

01:27:15.120 --> 01:27:22.120
[Amit Varma]: of formed and for what I've seen happening in India over the last couple of decades and

01:27:22.120 --> 01:27:25.600
[Amit Varma]: what you alluded to where people are more open with their prejudices, where they are

01:27:25.600 --> 01:27:30.320
[Amit Varma]: expressing their prejudices while earlier they would hide it. The sociologist Timur

01:27:30.320 --> 01:27:37.160
[Amit Varma]: Kuran wrote a book in 1999 called I think Public Lies and Private Truths where he coined

01:27:37.160 --> 01:27:42.160
[Amit Varma]: this phrase called preference falsification and one of the illustrations he gave was Soviet

01:27:42.160 --> 01:27:47.480
[Amit Varma]: Union where what happened was that everybody hated the state but nobody could say it because

01:27:47.480 --> 01:27:51.400
[Amit Varma]: a neighbor could you know tell on them. So they would keep it to themselves and that

01:27:51.400 --> 01:27:56.600
[Amit Varma]: was preference falsification and then one day suddenly the floodgates opened and everybody

01:27:56.600 --> 01:28:02.080
[Amit Varma]: found that hey everybody thinks like me and what took place was what Kuran calls a preference

01:28:02.080 --> 01:28:07.400
[Amit Varma]: cascade where suddenly everybody was free to express what they felt about the state

01:28:07.400 --> 01:28:13.240
[Amit Varma]: and almost overnight the Soviet Union kind of collapsed and there seems to be like one

01:28:13.240 --> 01:28:20.640
[Amit Varma]: of the reasons I think you know Modi came to power and so strongly and took such a stronghold

01:28:20.640 --> 01:28:26.960
[Amit Varma]: is that there has been a preference cascade now is that many people were what I call closet

01:28:26.960 --> 01:28:32.200
[Amit Varma]: bigots that many people had these prejudices they would not express it in polite society

01:28:32.200 --> 01:28:36.640
[Amit Varma]: because hey you know you thought that it won't go down well and all of that but then you

01:28:36.640 --> 01:28:40.960
[Amit Varma]: reach this turning point where you realize that you know the majority thinks like you.

01:28:40.960 --> 01:28:45.560
[Amit Varma]: It's okay in fact not only can you say these horrible things but they will win you brownie

01:28:45.560 --> 01:28:49.940
[Amit Varma]: points like you described listening to that speech of BP Singhal that that's probably

01:28:49.940 --> 01:28:55.680
[Amit Varma]: an early manifestation of that but today you know if you look at our politics you don't

01:28:55.680 --> 01:29:00.680
[Amit Varma]: need dog whistles anymore you know people will openly say things which they could only

01:29:00.680 --> 01:29:06.160
[Amit Varma]: have alluded to in the past and as for what is happening in our cities and of course in

01:29:06.160 --> 01:29:10.880
[Amit Varma]: Mumbai this is well documented various journalists over the years have done stories on how it's

01:29:10.880 --> 01:29:16.320
[Amit Varma]: hard for Muslims or single people or women or whatever to rent kind of flats in Mumbai

01:29:16.320 --> 01:29:20.960
[Amit Varma]: so I have a sort of larger question that I've thought about in the past I don't know even

01:29:20.960 --> 01:29:24.880
[Amit Varma]: know if it's a question or a lament and it's really for all my listeners to comment on

01:29:24.880 --> 01:29:31.520
[Amit Varma]: as much as for you is that you know if you look at the level of an individual flat owner

01:29:31.520 --> 01:29:36.480
[Amit Varma]: right she has a right to give her flat to whoever she wants so she can say that I want

01:29:36.480 --> 01:29:40.160
[Amit Varma]: people of my community only or I want people who won't cook non-veg because hey it's my

01:29:40.160 --> 01:29:46.520
[Amit Varma]: flat I don't like it and so on and so forth and at an individual level these individual

01:29:46.520 --> 01:29:53.320
[Amit Varma]: decisions get made but when we are a society with such prejudices then the overall outcome

01:29:53.320 --> 01:29:58.580
[Amit Varma]: can be really bad the overall outcome can be this sort of cloistering of different communities

01:29:58.580 --> 01:30:04.360
[Amit Varma]: in different areas which actually exacerbates these prejudices because then if you're a

01:30:04.360 --> 01:30:08.680
[Amit Varma]: you know a good vegetarian Hindu growing up in a middle-class household you're never encountering

01:30:08.680 --> 01:30:12.480
[Amit Varma]: another Muslim because they don't live anywhere around you and the prejudices deepen and they

01:30:12.480 --> 01:30:18.160
[Amit Varma]: become worse now you know this is not possible to police for and I don't think you know the

01:30:18.160 --> 01:30:23.240
[Amit Varma]: state should use coercion to sort of decide what people do with their individual flat

01:30:23.240 --> 01:30:28.320
[Amit Varma]: so it's a bunch of individuals making rational decisions which leads to an absolutely horrible

01:30:28.320 --> 01:30:34.160
[Amit Varma]: social outcome and the only way out therefore to me it would seem is that you have to change

01:30:34.160 --> 01:30:39.120
[Amit Varma]: it at the level of society where people feel differently about this but right now we are

01:30:39.120 --> 01:30:44.240
[Amit Varma]: stuck in this very bad equilibrium where there is where we are in a vicious circle there

01:30:44.240 --> 01:30:49.600
[Amit Varma]: is distrust and hate on all sides so I don't know the way out so it's not a question it's

01:30:49.600 --> 01:30:56.320
[Guest]: probably a lament do you have any thoughts on this you know I had heard Kefi Azbi at

01:30:56.320 --> 01:31:05.760
[Guest]: one of the Mushairas this was in the mid 90s and he said that if every Muslim has four

01:31:05.760 --> 01:31:11.360
[Guest]: or five Hindu friends and every Hindu has at least one or two Muslim friends this whole

01:31:11.360 --> 01:31:16.400
[Guest]: communal problem will end because then you get to see one another you get to grow up

01:31:16.400 --> 01:31:21.560
[Guest]: with one another and understand each other this is why I earlier when I was referring

01:31:21.560 --> 01:31:29.360
[Guest]: to my exposure to Hindi literature and Urdu literature because I realized that this Ganga

01:31:29.360 --> 01:31:36.520
[Guest]: Jamni that now has become a very bad word for a certain group of people this was a living

01:31:36.520 --> 01:31:43.440
[Guest]: reality it was not just limited to going to a festival to somebody's house it was something

01:31:43.440 --> 01:31:49.680
[Guest]: which was very organic to you you did not look at people by their religion you saw them

01:31:49.680 --> 01:31:56.360
[Guest]: by as your neighbor or you saw them as your business colleague or as a partner business

01:31:56.360 --> 01:32:01.840
[Guest]: partner or a shop where you trust the shop owner and you always buy your groceries from

01:32:01.840 --> 01:32:10.020
[Guest]: him or a vegetable vendor so it was very natural kind of intermingling of communities without

01:32:10.020 --> 01:32:16.040
[Guest]: any thought about a person's religion religion was in a private space even the namaz the

01:32:16.040 --> 01:32:22.000
[Guest]: azan which now has started bothering people nobody ever thought it was bothering them

01:32:22.000 --> 01:32:30.000
[Guest]: this five times a day call through a loudspeaker it was very organic to a city nobody minded

01:32:30.000 --> 01:32:35.520
[Guest]: it and nobody ever thought that it was impinging in their private or personal space or the

01:32:35.520 --> 01:32:41.440
[Guest]: jagarans nobody thought anything about it but now all of these have become irritant

01:32:41.440 --> 01:32:50.160
[Guest]: and all of them have become irritants to a degree that people relate their old grievances

01:32:50.160 --> 01:32:54.400
[Guest]: linked to this that oh we've been suffering this for years but you did not they did not

01:32:54.400 --> 01:32:59.960
[Guest]: suffer this they they did not even notice it it was so much part of your life so this

01:32:59.960 --> 01:33:04.800
[Guest]: is what is happening now what you just said that if you don't give your house you don't

01:33:04.800 --> 01:33:10.400
[Guest]: get to see another muslim this is also true of muslims see if you're forcing muslims to

01:33:10.400 --> 01:33:15.960
[Guest]: live in a ghetto then these muslims they do not see people from another community so you

01:33:15.960 --> 01:33:21.960
[Guest]: are driven by your own prejudice but you are in turn also helping another community develop

01:33:21.960 --> 01:33:29.640
[Guest]: their own prejudices there are people in the okla or area or batla house area the jamia

01:33:29.640 --> 01:33:36.560
[Guest]: area who never encounter a non-muslim at all in their lives they they are born in that

01:33:36.560 --> 01:33:41.400
[Guest]: area and they go to the local hospital there where the childbirth happens they go to the

01:33:41.400 --> 01:33:46.200
[Guest]: local school there then they go to the college or an institute or whatever there if they

01:33:46.200 --> 01:33:51.240
[Guest]: don't if they can afford to go to the university they go to the jamia university or if they

01:33:51.240 --> 01:33:58.640
[Guest]: can't afford that then they just get into the workforce uh in that area so their exposure

01:33:58.640 --> 01:34:05.920
[Guest]: to anybody outside the community is minimal so while you are trying to insulate yourself

01:34:05.920 --> 01:34:13.600
[Guest]: from the outsiders you think they are dirty or they are oppressors or we have suffered

01:34:13.600 --> 01:34:20.920
[Guest]: for thousands of years because of them but you are actually imperiling yourself even

01:34:20.920 --> 01:34:26.000
[Guest]: further because instead of you trying to understand them and them trying to understand you you

01:34:26.000 --> 01:34:32.040
[Guest]: are actually furthering this distance even more so your prejudice is getting reinforced

01:34:32.040 --> 01:34:37.000
[Guest]: but the other person's prejudice is also getting reinforced and add to that other person's

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:43.720
[Guest]: prejudice is also genuine grievance for not getting a fair chance a genuine complaint

01:34:43.720 --> 01:34:53.560
[Guest]: that the law enforcement agencies the are biased towards them so these are or these

01:34:53.560 --> 01:34:58.760
[Guest]: should be matter of concern for any country that you are dispossessing a huge chunk of

01:34:58.760 --> 01:35:06.000
[Guest]: your population how can you even imagine that despite this dispossession you can still develop

01:35:06.000 --> 01:35:11.920
[Guest]: you can still grow you can your GDP will grow when such a huge chunk of your population

01:35:11.920 --> 01:35:17.440
[Guest]: is disaffected it is not part of your mainstream it is not contributing to your mainstream

01:35:17.440 --> 01:35:25.640
[Guest]: this human resource is being is uh underemployed it is not being harnessed uh for nation building

01:35:25.640 --> 01:35:31.720
[Guest]: how do you even imagine that you can still manage to do well with this in fact if you're

01:35:31.720 --> 01:35:36.400
[Amit Varma]: talking of human resources not just a minority community it's all women basically the way

01:35:36.400 --> 01:35:40.920
[Amit Varma]: women are like second class citizens in india and can't you know reach their true potential

01:35:40.920 --> 01:35:45.600
[Amit Varma]: and you know i had done in a sort of an episode with anchal malhotra a very moving episode

01:35:45.600 --> 01:35:50.440
[Amit Varma]: and partition and you know one of the thoughts that came to us while we were in conversation

01:35:50.440 --> 01:35:56.280
[Amit Varma]: there was this difference between the abstract and the concrete that when we speak of all

01:35:56.280 --> 01:36:01.840
[Amit Varma]: this hatred that is there within people all this animosity towards the other as it were

01:36:01.840 --> 01:36:07.080
[Amit Varma]: all of it is in an abstract realm in the concrete realm they can be perfectly good people they

01:36:07.080 --> 01:36:11.920
[Amit Varma]: can be friendly they can be assimilative and all of that but in an abstract realm that's

01:36:11.920 --> 01:36:17.000
[Amit Varma]: where all these concepts like nationalism and you know hindu purity and that sense of

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:21.040
[Amit Varma]: historical victimhood though they have never been victims themselves all of that comes

01:36:21.040 --> 01:36:26.200
[Amit Varma]: into play and therefore it strikes me that what you need really to bring people together

01:36:26.200 --> 01:36:30.440
[Amit Varma]: is more of the concrete and less of the abstract and like you pointed out that if you are not

01:36:30.440 --> 01:36:34.400
[Amit Varma]: exposed to the other at all if a hindu will have no muslim friends or a muslim will have

01:36:34.400 --> 01:36:39.680
[Amit Varma]: no hindu friends then there is none of that concrete where you know you can just look

01:36:39.680 --> 01:36:43.320
[Amit Varma]: across the table and you see someone just like you and therefore the abstract concept

01:36:43.320 --> 01:36:49.160
[Amit Varma]: doesn't matter so much and and that's kind of a little tragic and if anything it's you

01:36:49.160 --> 01:36:57.000
[Amit Varma]: know outside our elite bubbles i think it's only increased you know over the years see

01:36:57.000 --> 01:37:03.600
[Guest]: there's another thing here sometimes we are so happy and we know that our abstract is

01:37:03.600 --> 01:37:12.080
[Guest]: actually a bubble it's so vulnerable to a hard gaze that we do not even question what

01:37:12.080 --> 01:37:17.320
[Guest]: we have inherited the prejudice that we are living with because we know if we look at

01:37:17.320 --> 01:37:25.880
[Guest]: it or if we question it it'll all come crashing down because there's no basis to it it's just

01:37:25.880 --> 01:37:32.000
[Guest]: probably a insecurity that has been fanned for so long that it has become some sort of

01:37:32.000 --> 01:37:44.240
[Guest]: a concretized stone on your heart or in your mind or it's it's probably just economic vulnerability

01:37:44.240 --> 01:37:49.840
[Guest]: you just feel so insecure in your own self that you feel that if i share this space with

01:37:49.840 --> 01:37:55.600
[Guest]: somebody else probably this opportunity will be taken away from me so that could be one

01:37:55.600 --> 01:38:01.960
[Amit Varma]: of the reasons yeah that's a fascinating point i mean in a poor country you know people

01:38:01.960 --> 01:38:05.920
[Amit Varma]: tend to think more in zero-sum ways because there is scarcity you know otherwise of course

01:38:05.920 --> 01:38:10.280
[Amit Varma]: all human interaction is positive sum you know i buy something from you both of us benefit

01:38:10.280 --> 01:38:14.000
[Amit Varma]: that's why we are having that transaction but where there is scarcity where there are

01:38:14.000 --> 01:38:19.200
[Amit Varma]: limited opportunities and resources there people tend to think of it as a zero-sum game

01:38:19.200 --> 01:38:23.480
[Amit Varma]: if somebody else wins something that means you have lost which you know goes into many

01:38:23.480 --> 01:38:28.280
[Amit Varma]: other contexts apart from just money and i guess that is again one factor that could

01:38:28.280 --> 01:38:33.640
[Amit Varma]: have be fueling this in a country like india we'll take a quick commercial break now and

01:38:33.640 --> 01:38:38.180
[Amit Varma]: when we come back you know we've spoken so far about sort of your personal impressions

01:38:38.180 --> 01:38:42.520
[Amit Varma]: and your life and all of that over this period of time but your book is also a fabulous book

01:38:42.520 --> 01:38:47.000
[Amit Varma]: of scholarship you know there's so much i learned about the history of islam in india

01:38:47.000 --> 01:38:49.720
[Amit Varma]: though i'm fairly well read in history but there were a lot of things which i hadn't

01:38:49.720 --> 01:38:54.120
[Amit Varma]: known earlier which i'd really love to get into but let's take a quick commercial break

01:38:54.120 --> 01:39:01.760
[Amit Varma]: and after that we shall continue this conversation long before i was a podcaster i was a writer

01:39:01.760 --> 01:39:06.920
[Amit Varma]: in fact chances are that many of you first heard of me because of my blog india uncut

01:39:06.920 --> 01:39:12.360
[Amit Varma]: which was active between 2003 and 2009 and became somewhat popular at the time i love

01:39:12.360 --> 01:39:17.800
[Amit Varma]: the freedom the form gave me and i feel i was shaped by it in many ways i exercise my

01:39:17.800 --> 01:39:22.160
[Amit Varma]: writing muscle every day and was forced to think about many different things because

01:39:22.160 --> 01:39:27.200
[Amit Varma]: i wrote about many different things well that phase in my life ended for various reasons

01:39:27.200 --> 01:39:32.480
