01:41:34.440 --> 01:41:41.440
[Guest]: that time because it had not started to expand beyond its territory during the prophet's

01:41:41.440 --> 01:41:50.080
[Guest]: lifetime that happened after his death and with the first khalifa which was abu akr so

01:41:50.080 --> 01:41:58.480
[Guest]: that is when the muslim armies or soldiers were moving out but in india because the trade

01:41:58.480 --> 01:42:03.800
[Guest]: route was already there and these traders were now muslims so when when you're coming

01:42:03.800 --> 01:42:09.920
[Guest]: by sea you're actually out of your home for months and sometimes years and sometimes you

01:42:09.920 --> 01:42:16.400
[Guest]: don't even know if you're coming back so they obviously would be accompanied by some religious

01:42:16.400 --> 01:42:23.160
[Guest]: people who could give them support or succor or somebody who could lead the prayer because

01:42:23.160 --> 01:42:30.320
[Guest]: in islam a prayer for men is led by a prayer leader i mean women can pray on their own

01:42:30.320 --> 01:42:35.520
[Guest]: but for men which is why the concept of going to a mosque and praying together which is

01:42:35.520 --> 01:42:40.240
[Guest]: why mosques have to be huge spaces even if they're not constructed spaces they have to

01:42:40.240 --> 01:42:46.200
[Guest]: be huge spaces because men are required to trade together in a congregation led by a

01:42:46.200 --> 01:42:55.880
[Guest]: prayer leader so the religious preachers started accompanying these trading caravans a lot

01:42:55.880 --> 01:43:02.160
[Guest]: of people settled down there in the preachers was preaching to the local people some converted

01:43:02.160 --> 01:43:08.400
[Guest]: some didn't convert but even if you didn't convert if you've just felt some sort of peace

01:43:08.400 --> 01:43:14.720
[Guest]: some sort of happiness talking to a person you automatically start veering towards that

01:43:14.720 --> 01:43:21.680
[Guest]: person so the early islam which came to india it came through these mendicants who would

01:43:21.680 --> 01:43:29.680
[Guest]: set up a small cottage or a place outside the city zones or village or on the outskirts

01:43:29.680 --> 01:43:34.400
[Guest]: and people would start coming to them because they found peace there or some sort of comfort

01:43:34.400 --> 01:43:43.680
[Guest]: gradually the population in a very organic manner started growing in this entire coastal

01:43:43.680 --> 01:43:50.520
[Guest]: belt the malabar belt but it was along the coastline because probably they were also

01:43:50.520 --> 01:43:57.280
[Guest]: worried of going too much in the hinterland that happened over the next few centuries

01:43:57.280 --> 01:44:03.680
[Guest]: i think by the 9th century they had moved much further inside because there was a lot

01:44:03.680 --> 01:44:13.120
[Guest]: of intermarriage was happening then the king there were the paramil kings there they converted

01:44:13.120 --> 01:44:21.000
[Guest]: to islam and once the ruler converted to islam then obviously there was this huge umbrella

01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:28.880
[Guest]: of royal patronage which was given to the muslim preachers so they moved further inland

01:44:28.880 --> 01:44:39.040
[Guest]: and that is when this was the first cycle of islam coming into india at the same time

01:44:39.040 --> 01:44:47.600
[Guest]: there was another route sea route which was coming to kutch and this was also traders

01:44:47.600 --> 01:44:52.720
[Guest]: businessmen who were coming there working there some settled down there some married

01:44:52.720 --> 01:45:00.840
[Guest]: local women the first invader was muhammad bin qasim who came but if you read tarajan's

01:45:00.840 --> 01:45:10.040
[Guest]: history of in middle in india he says that he came because there was and by this time

01:45:10.040 --> 01:45:17.680
[Guest]: islam had spread to sri lanka also so there were some orphan muslim who were there in

01:45:17.680 --> 01:45:23.560
[Guest]: sri lanka the parents had died and there was like a group of orphans and so they wanted

01:45:23.560 --> 01:45:33.440
[Guest]: to go back to arabia so this ship was hijacked by the gujarat-based pirates and these kids

01:45:33.440 --> 01:45:43.200
[Guest]: were taken away so the caliphate then the governor of basra then he sent a damash to

01:45:43.200 --> 01:45:51.840
[Guest]: the king of this region and he said you return the kids and so there was a face-off and then

01:45:51.840 --> 01:46:00.840
[Guest]: muhammad bin qasim was tasked to go and rescue the kids so that's how he came leading a army

01:46:00.840 --> 01:46:09.240
[Guest]: and that was the first invasion but he came here he defeated the local king dahir he plundered

01:46:09.240 --> 01:46:14.680
[Guest]: did whatever and plundering was a very natural part if you're going somewhere you have to

01:46:14.680 --> 01:46:19.560
[Guest]: pay for your journey to and back i mean if it doesn't make economic sense to you why

01:46:19.560 --> 01:46:28.600
[Guest]: would you go there so they he did some plundering and he returned to arabia so that was the

01:46:28.600 --> 01:46:37.840
[Guest]: first invasion that happened but that invasion didn't create a empire or a dynasty or any

01:46:37.840 --> 01:46:46.920
[Guest]: such thing he came he went away and this trade continued the in our perception of muslim

01:46:46.920 --> 01:46:53.520
[Guest]: invaders we actually do not look at all this with so much of emphasis we look at the invaders

01:46:53.520 --> 01:47:02.200
[Guest]: from afghanistan we look at gauri and ghazni because these are the people who left lasting

01:47:02.200 --> 01:47:13.120
[Guest]: impact on the indian population the indian society but the lasting impact or even greater

01:47:13.120 --> 01:47:19.360
[Guest]: impact was led left by the business community the traders but because that doesn't give

01:47:19.360 --> 01:47:29.840
[Guest]: us much room for vilification so that part or the coming of sufis and the how the how

01:47:29.840 --> 01:47:36.680
[Guest]: islam spread through sufis that part we kind of whitewash we only focus on the invaders

01:47:36.680 --> 01:47:44.600
[Guest]: but invaders was only one part of coming of islam to india and actually invaders were

01:47:44.600 --> 01:47:49.920
[Guest]: individuals who were pursuing their political ambitions they were not really ambassadors

01:47:49.920 --> 01:47:55.480
[Guest]: of islam they were not coming here to spread islam so subsequently even gauri was trying

01:47:55.480 --> 01:48:01.920
[Guest]: to become a muslim you know mujahid and he made the petition to the abbasid caliphate

01:48:01.920 --> 01:48:09.880
[Guest]: and said i'm spreading islam but he was far too debauched for the caliphate to consider

01:48:09.880 --> 01:48:16.520
[Guest]: him as actually a mujahid i mean he was not really islamic warrior so a lot of warriors

01:48:16.520 --> 01:48:22.760
[Guest]: also or a lot of invaders subsequently you know belatedly realized the importance of

01:48:22.760 --> 01:48:30.680
[Guest]: claiming the title of being crusaders for islam or mujahids people who are waiting jihad

01:48:30.680 --> 01:48:37.160
[Guest]: because they felt that it would accrue them some religious benefits though they were amassing

01:48:37.160 --> 01:48:42.000
[Guest]: wealth and they were completely against the principles or the key founding principles

01:48:42.000 --> 01:48:46.800
[Guest]: of islam but they thought it would accrue them some benefits but they can carry some

01:48:46.800 --> 01:48:55.880
[Guest]: favors with the caliphate so that is how islam came to india the first empire which was set

01:48:55.880 --> 01:49:01.960
[Guest]: up here was a slave dynasty which had two prongs one was in bengal which was the bengal

01:49:01.960 --> 01:49:08.680
[Guest]: sultanate and the other was established in delhi and north india which was a delhi sultanate

01:49:08.680 --> 01:49:15.120
[Guest]: so while the bengal sultanate went further east went up to assam and other parts of the

01:49:15.120 --> 01:49:22.200
[Guest]: north eastern states in addition to the whole of bengal the delhi sultanate apart from north

01:49:22.200 --> 01:49:31.040
[Guest]: india they and during the reign of alauddin kilji they started moving further south so

01:49:31.040 --> 01:49:39.920
[Guest]: the first campaigns in the deccan were carried out by alauddin kilji's commander-in-chief

01:49:39.920 --> 01:49:50.000
[Guest]: that i'm forgetting the name kafur whatever his name is malik kafur so interestingly these

01:49:50.000 --> 01:49:57.600
[Guest]: were the afghan people of afghan origin but with a lot of persian influences so these

01:49:57.600 --> 01:50:08.120
[Guest]: were not arabs the islam which people in kerala and parts of karnataka tamil nadu even the

01:50:08.120 --> 01:50:15.440
[Guest]: slight the northern conk and belt the the kind of islam that they were familiar with

01:50:15.440 --> 01:50:22.440
[Guest]: or they were practicing was the arabized islam which came to the arab traders but when malik

01:50:22.440 --> 01:50:30.440
[Guest]: kafur's campaign succeeded and he conquered these territories so there was this amalgamation

01:50:30.440 --> 01:50:42.200
[Guest]: of persianized afghan central asian sort of culture language food and there was this arabized

01:50:42.200 --> 01:50:48.520
[Guest]: sort of a thing so if you see this belt there was a confluence of both these influences

01:50:48.520 --> 01:50:55.160
[Guest]: which is why the islam practiced in the southern part of india is very distinct from what we

01:50:55.160 --> 01:51:02.240
[Guest]: do in north india there's a very clear i mean not only language and culture but even to

01:51:02.240 --> 01:51:09.080
[Guest]: some extent in what they believe to be religious practices so there's a difference because

