[Amit Varma]: and a little later you write something which leads me to my next question where you write

01:52:42.820 --> 01:52:46.960
[Amit Varma]: quote their pace of growth was more rapid in the south as compared to the western central

01:52:46.960 --> 01:52:52.040
[Amit Varma]: regions primarily because there was great religious social and political turmoil in

01:52:52.040 --> 01:52:55.820
[Amit Varma]: southern india during the eighth and ninth centuries there was a tussle for supremacy

01:52:55.820 --> 01:53:00.580
[Amit Varma]: between hinduism buddhism and jainism in addition the old kingdoms were in disarray in the face

01:53:00.580 --> 01:53:05.800
[Amit Varma]: of new claimants to power into this situation islam appeared upon the scene with a simple

01:53:05.800 --> 01:53:11.840
[Amit Varma]: formula of faith well-defined dogmas and rights and democratic theories of social reorganization

01:53:11.840 --> 01:53:15.880
[Amit Varma]: it produced a tremendous effect stop quote and my questionnaire is this that you know

01:53:15.880 --> 01:53:23.040
[Amit Varma]: when i read this i was sort of thinking about the power of narratives in cultural dominance

01:53:23.040 --> 01:53:30.320
[Amit Varma]: and one of the things that struck me here is that people are drawn to simple narratives

01:53:30.320 --> 01:53:34.560
[Amit Varma]: complex narratives are too complex as it were they want simple explanations of the world

01:53:34.560 --> 01:53:39.080
[Amit Varma]: and it strikes me that islam what it would have provided with its certainties with this

01:53:39.080 --> 01:53:43.680
[Amit Varma]: linear strand of what happens where and you don't have a hundred gods and you don't have

01:53:43.680 --> 01:53:49.320
[Amit Varma]: all of that would have provided a simple narrative which you can immediately understand and internalize

01:53:49.320 --> 01:53:54.520
[Amit Varma]: as opposed to its competitors and i say its competitors because you know there is a school

01:53:54.520 --> 01:53:59.540
[Amit Varma]: of thought that hinduism is not some monolithic thing as we know it today that was partly

01:53:59.540 --> 01:54:04.720
[Amit Varma]: a construct of you know when the british came their early interlocutors were the apakas

01:54:04.720 --> 01:54:08.760
[Amit Varma]: brahmins and the apakas brahmins sold them this version of hinduism as you know the varna

01:54:08.760 --> 01:54:14.080
[Amit Varma]: system and the manusmriti hinduism basically and they extrapolated that to the whole subcontinent

01:54:14.080 --> 01:54:18.640
[Amit Varma]: but actually there were many many many different traditions within hinduism and they would

01:54:18.640 --> 01:54:25.600
[Amit Varma]: all have been very complicated and all of that and islam comes along and one you are

01:54:25.600 --> 01:54:29.720
[Amit Varma]: supposed to be zealous about spreading the faith and two you've got a really simple narrative

01:54:29.720 --> 01:54:34.120
[Amit Varma]: like one of my and i'm not making a value judgment on simple narratives one way or the

01:54:34.120 --> 01:54:38.000
[Amit Varma]: other that they are necessary sometimes they are good sometimes they are misleading like

01:54:38.000 --> 01:54:42.800
[Amit Varma]: i once speculated that one of the reasons trump won in 2016 was he had a simple narrative

01:54:42.800 --> 01:54:47.080
[Amit Varma]: it was wrong but it was simple and sometimes that's an important thing and perhaps you

01:54:47.080 --> 01:54:50.880
[Amit Varma]: could argue the dispensation and power in india has a simple narrative as well it's

01:54:50.880 --> 01:54:54.640
[Amit Varma]: wrong but simple you know it doesn't embrace the complexities do you think there's something

01:54:54.640 --> 01:55:01.360
[Guest]: to that i agree islam had a very simple narrative added to that simple narrative was a very

01:55:01.360 --> 01:55:09.520
[Guest]: laid down structured form of practicing of religion so there were five pillars very easy

01:55:09.520 --> 01:55:15.800
[Guest]: to remember one was the kalma which every which just two lines that you memorize it

01:55:15.800 --> 01:55:21.000
[Guest]: and the kalma itself is proclamation of your religion that okay i am a muslim now so even

01:55:21.000 --> 01:55:25.480
[Guest]: today if a person has to convert to islam all he has to do is recite the kalma and you

01:55:25.480 --> 01:55:31.200
[Guest]: are converted there is no ritual happening there is no process of becoming a muslim it's

01:55:31.200 --> 01:55:37.280
[Guest]: as simple as reciting of a kalma then you have prayers five times a day again very simple

01:55:37.280 --> 01:55:43.800
[Guest]: and the prayer times are fixed what the first prayer is that before dawn then there is just

01:55:43.800 --> 01:55:49.760
[Guest]: before the noon hour that is zawal period then you have pre-dusk then you have dusk

01:55:49.760 --> 01:55:57.480
[Guest]: and you have night prayer very simple laid down prayer time then similarly ramzan you

01:55:57.480 --> 01:56:05.040
[Guest]: have a month in a year where you fast from dawn to dusk very simple no complication and

01:56:05.040 --> 01:56:12.760
[Guest]: hajj if you are able-bodied if you're financially solvent you can do it you go for hajj and

01:56:12.760 --> 01:56:18.160
[Guest]: the most important is zakat now again zakat is a such a noble thing to do that anybody

01:56:18.160 --> 01:56:24.960
[Guest]: would be would really believe and rightly so that a good part of your faith is helping

01:56:24.960 --> 01:56:30.160
[Guest]: others so now there's an integral to faith that you have to help others it's not a choice

01:56:30.160 --> 01:56:38.280
[Guest]: you're not uh it's not left to an individual's judgment so these were the five pillars now

01:56:38.280 --> 01:56:42.720
[Guest]: over the years what has happened you have islamic jurisprudence you have this law that

01:56:42.720 --> 01:56:48.280
[Guest]: law all that is later edition but when you're appealing to a non-muslim this is these are

01:56:48.280 --> 01:56:57.960
[Guest]: the five pillars very simple systematic way of becoming a muslim and if you see this it's

01:56:57.960 --> 01:57:06.240
[Guest]: not even very complicated to practice i mean now hardline muslim ulemas would insist that

01:57:06.240 --> 01:57:14.200
[Guest]: you do prayer in a particular way you have to bend in a particular way but traditionally

01:57:14.200 --> 01:57:19.760
[Guest]: nobody interrupted in the way you practice your religion the biggest factor in favor

01:57:19.760 --> 01:57:26.280
[Guest]: of islam at that point which would have appeared to people who were converting then was lack

01:57:26.280 --> 01:57:33.960
[Guest]: of clergy absence of clergy there was no religious leader that you had to go to there was nobody

01:57:33.960 --> 01:57:40.480
[Guest]: who would tell you with authority or impose upon you his or her writ that this is how

01:57:40.480 --> 01:57:48.160
[Guest]: you have to do it islam sunni islam said it is between you and your allah so you do whatever

01:57:48.160 --> 01:57:53.680
[Guest]: you want to do as long as your conscience is clear nobody has any business to interrupt

01:57:53.680 --> 01:58:01.600
[Guest]: or tell you that you're doing something wrong so in a society where you had such rigid clergy

01:58:01.600 --> 01:58:06.360
[Guest]: it's not just india i mean even uh in the entire christian world where you had such

01:58:06.360 --> 01:58:14.720
[Guest]: rigid clergy and when people were expected to be uh referential towards the clergy defer

01:58:14.720 --> 01:58:22.480
[Guest]: to their vims and their orders uh spend so much money uh in keeping the clergy happy

01:58:22.480 --> 01:58:35.800
[Guest]: so this looked like a very simple and humane sort of a religion where you're also factoring

01:58:35.800 --> 01:58:41.880
[Guest]: in looking after a fellow muslim you know there's an islamic saying which is not part

01:58:41.880 --> 01:58:46.720
[Guest]: of the quran but it is part of the islamic saying that every muslim is responsible for

01:58:46.720 --> 01:58:56.360
[Guest]: uh 40 households in his neighborhood so 10 in each direction so if uh even one person

01:58:56.360 --> 01:59:02.280
[Guest]: in this neighborhood of 40 households that every person is responsible to dies of starvation

01:59:02.280 --> 01:59:08.720
[Guest]: that sin is upon you how was it that you didn't come to know that somebody was hungry so if

01:59:08.720 --> 01:59:16.560
[Guest]: each is responsible for 40 uh so it's it's a cycle it's a circle uh which kind of grows

01:59:16.560 --> 01:59:24.960
[Guest]: so with this sort of uh approach and then the sufis very uh selfless poor people who

01:59:24.960 --> 01:59:30.800
[Guest]: want nothing for themselves they live in uh poor circumstances they hold these open kitchens

01:59:30.800 --> 01:59:37.240
[Guest]: for people to feed people every day all this is very appealing you know as a person you

01:59:37.240 --> 01:59:44.040
[Guest]: would just get drawn to something which appears so selfless so the politics of the religion

01:59:44.040 --> 01:59:50.000
[Guest]: uh it surfaced much later i mean there was a lot of politics of religion even in arabia

01:59:50.000 --> 01:59:54.960
[Guest]: at that time but when you're reaching out to people this politics doesn't show itself

01:59:54.960 --> 02:00:03.880
[Guest]: you show yourself uh with your best foot forward and this is what it how it appears to people

02:00:03.880 --> 02:00:08.760
[Amit Varma]: yeah and and you know in the popular imagination these days people will look upon uh those

02:00:08.760 --> 02:00:14.240
[Amit Varma]: sort of years of you know slave dynasty followed by the mughal dynasty and all of that as mughals

02:00:14.240 --> 02:00:18.640
[Amit Varma]: are coming and they've subjugated the local people but that was far from the case uh whoever

02:00:18.640 --> 02:00:23.520
[Amit Varma]: might politically have been in charge uh the you know muslims and hindus work together

02:00:23.520 --> 02:00:28.640
