[Amit Varma]: it another way we are a deeply liberal society in terms of our lived life the way that there

03:22:51.000 --> 03:22:55.800
[Amit Varma]: is a lift tolerance there we assimilate so much from so many cultures and all of that

03:22:55.800 --> 03:23:00.420
[Amit Varma]: and i get it that there is a stand of that also now when i look back on indian history

03:23:00.420 --> 03:23:05.720
[Amit Varma]: in the last sort of hundred years what what kind of strikes me is that what is happening

03:23:05.720 --> 03:23:12.280
[Amit Varma]: today while it has come to our politics this sort of othering of muslims and this very

03:23:12.280 --> 03:23:17.360
[Amit Varma]: toxic polarizing politics while it's come to our politics today while it's gained dominance

03:23:17.360 --> 03:23:22.100
[Amit Varma]: in our politics today rather it's always been in our culture something that i got a slightly

03:23:22.100 --> 03:23:25.780
[Amit Varma]: deeper realization of when i did an episode with akshay mukul who's written a brilliant

03:23:25.780 --> 03:23:30.680
[Amit Varma]: book on the gita press and one sees that you know when you look at the bhagavad you know

03:23:30.680 --> 03:23:34.440
[Amit Varma]: their version of the bhagavad gita selling 70 million copies and the kind of things that

03:23:34.440 --> 03:23:38.400
[Amit Varma]: they sell not just the bhagavad gita which anyway everyone should read it's a great book

03:23:38.400 --> 03:23:43.440
[Amit Varma]: regardless or whatever but the other kind of stuff that they sell including uh you know

03:23:43.440 --> 03:23:49.440
[Amit Varma]: much of like you know what i learned from reading his book was how old these campaigns

03:23:49.440 --> 03:23:53.360
[Amit Varma]: like love jihad and the campaign against cow slaughter and all of those actually are it's

03:23:53.360 --> 03:23:57.880
[Amit Varma]: not something new it's they've gained dominance in politics recently but they've been around

03:23:57.880 --> 03:24:02.840
[Amit Varma]: in culture for a long time and my sort of sense and the sense that kind of gives me

03:24:02.840 --> 03:24:08.140
[Amit Varma]: some hope is that we all contain multitudes so therefore somebody who might on the one

03:24:08.140 --> 03:24:13.880
[Amit Varma]: hand be drawn by abstract notions of nationalism or india is for the hindus or whatever might

03:24:13.880 --> 03:24:20.720
[Amit Varma]: also have other aspects to her personality which are much more tolerant and assimilative

03:24:20.720 --> 03:24:27.440
[Amit Varma]: and therefore uh you know one hopeful hypothesis is that what currently uh the people in power

03:24:27.440 --> 03:24:32.180
[Amit Varma]: have managed to appeal to and what has currently become the dominant narrative strand is this

03:24:32.180 --> 03:24:37.400
[Amit Varma]: particular strand but there are other strands which are possible because there are you know

03:24:37.400 --> 03:24:42.480
[Amit Varma]: we do contain multitudes we are illiberal but at the same time we are liberal what is

03:24:42.480 --> 03:24:47.680
[Amit Varma]: your take on that you know is there uh you know like someone once said whatever you say

03:24:47.680 --> 03:24:53.180
[Amit Varma]: of india the opposite is also true so is that something that you'd agree with is that something

03:24:53.180 --> 03:24:56.960
[Amit Varma]: that you know i i know that we can look all around us and there is a lot to give us the

03:24:56.960 --> 03:25:01.580
[Amit Varma]: spare are there also things that give you hope and feel that at a cultural level because

03:25:01.580 --> 03:25:06.720
[Amit Varma]: it has to change at a cultural level first before anything else changes at a cultural

03:25:06.720 --> 03:25:12.280
[Amit Varma]: level is there hope that say the better angels of our nature so to say can express themselves

03:25:12.280 --> 03:25:19.320
[Guest]: what is your sense of this uh i i completely agree we are actually there's a huge dichotomy

03:25:19.320 --> 03:25:25.320
[Guest]: between in our country we have always been very tolerant of outsiders at one level but

03:25:25.320 --> 03:25:31.980
[Guest]: we have also been xenophobic i mean we have been very liberal in our approach to a lot

03:25:31.980 --> 03:25:40.640
[Guest]: of issues acceptance of others being one of them tolerance of everybody whether it's you

03:25:40.640 --> 03:25:46.400
[Guest]: know even gay i mean now there has been a bit of homophobia around i mean there has

03:25:46.400 --> 03:25:50.600
[Guest]: been a strand of homophobia but there has been acceptance and it's part been part of

03:25:50.600 --> 03:25:57.720
[Guest]: our culture we have been very very reverential about women in certain matters and i'm not

03:25:57.720 --> 03:26:05.040
[Guest]: talking about worship but we have been accepting of women leadership also and not just in politics

03:26:05.040 --> 03:26:10.840
[Guest]: but in other parts of our lives also whether it's businesses business houses or in within

03:26:10.840 --> 03:26:20.160
[Guest]: the family and then we have cases of complete horrific violence against women so we kind

03:26:20.160 --> 03:26:26.520
[Guest]: of inhabit both worlds but uh coming to your question specific question about what gives

03:26:26.520 --> 03:26:36.440
[Guest]: you hope i think the recent example of this caa nrc protest which broke out or which started

03:26:36.440 --> 03:26:43.440
[Guest]: in uh shaheen bagh and it kind of sprouted in all parts of india and it was essentially

03:26:43.440 --> 03:26:50.680
[Guest]: driven by a muslim's insecurity about their place in india whether they'll be declared

03:26:50.680 --> 03:26:59.520
[Guest]: as non-indians and shoved into some camp but the kind of support that it garnered from

03:26:59.520 --> 03:27:05.920
[Guest]: all sorts of people even people who were no not known to be activists they came out on

03:27:05.920 --> 03:27:13.840
[Guest]: the streets to uh support this assault on what they called constitution but assault

03:27:13.840 --> 03:27:19.360
[Guest]: on constitution again is an abstract vague concept essentially on the ground what was

03:27:19.360 --> 03:27:26.480
[Guest]: happening was assault on a community based on their religion and you see people who had

03:27:26.480 --> 03:27:33.680
[Guest]: no familiarity with the urdu poetry were singing faiz emad faiz and there were people who had

03:27:33.680 --> 03:27:42.080
[Guest]: memorized it and actually it's not an easy to learn and it's not easy to understand also

03:27:42.080 --> 03:27:49.760
[Guest]: besides it has a very strong islamic imagery i mean though it's not a religious poem but

03:27:49.760 --> 03:27:55.920
[Guest]: it has a strong islamic imagery which goes back to the time of the prophet so uh despite

03:27:55.920 --> 03:28:05.320
[Guest]: that people were saying that so i think that all this shows that there is a sustained pushback

03:28:05.320 --> 03:28:10.200
[Guest]: in whatever way you know if you're faced with police and police is completely compromised

03:28:10.200 --> 03:28:15.400
[Guest]: and they're hitting out at you it's very difficult and it's not fair also to expect that people

03:28:15.400 --> 03:28:22.620
[Guest]: will will continuously be standing against uh this sort of violence but this pushback

03:28:22.620 --> 03:28:31.000
[Guest]: this uh even emotional agitation which uh happened among a lot of people and non-muslims

03:28:31.000 --> 03:28:39.200
[Guest]: it's very it's i encouraging is a very condescending word it is something which tells you that

03:28:39.200 --> 03:28:48.200
[Guest]: uh this rss outreach it's not been a completely successful project that despite uh they're

03:28:48.200 --> 03:28:57.560
[Guest]: trying to kind of build a narrative in their own way uh it has not percolated down to the

03:28:57.560 --> 03:29:03.760
[Guest]: last citizen of the country there are people who are still thinking and resisting because

03:29:03.760 --> 03:29:12.800
[Guest]: they feel that this is not what uh india is or this is not what india stands for i think

03:29:12.800 --> 03:29:19.920
[Guest]: this is this has been a huge moment i i am also not a activist by temperament i am a

03:29:19.920 --> 03:29:28.560
[Guest]: very uh quite a sort of a person i like to be on my own i like being on my own quietly

03:29:28.560 --> 03:29:34.200
[Guest]: sitting in one corner and just thinking about things and daydreaming or i'm not a very social

03:29:34.200 --> 03:29:39.300
[Guest]: person but when all this was happening and i was reading up stuff and i was watching

03:29:39.300 --> 03:29:45.680
[Guest]: videos it was something which was filling me up with this huge desire to go out there

03:29:45.680 --> 03:29:50.760
[Guest]: and maybe i should also stand with them and do something maybe uh i'm wasting my life

03:29:50.760 --> 03:29:57.520
[Guest]: just sitting in my study and doing nothing uh so that sort of momentum which it created

03:29:57.520 --> 03:30:04.040
[Guest]: i think in it has been unparalleled in recent times and this is what is happening now with

03:30:04.040 --> 03:30:10.840
[Guest]: the farmers protest also so probably things will not change in a hurry but as long as

03:30:10.840 --> 03:30:16.360
[Guest]: this resistance is there as long as there are people who believe that they need to stand

03:30:16.360 --> 03:30:23.280
[Guest]: up and be counted whatever the consequences we shouldn't despair no very wise words and

03:30:23.280 --> 03:30:27.280
[Amit Varma]: and as an aside you mentioned daydreaming now and earlier and it struck me when you

03:30:27.280 --> 03:30:31.160
[Amit Varma]: mentioned it earlier that i'm also a huge daydreamer to the point that you know when

03:30:31.160 --> 03:30:35.560
[Amit Varma]: i first read james serber's famous short story the secret life of walter mitty i thought

03:30:35.560 --> 03:30:39.520
[Amit Varma]: that what is a big deal about this aren't we all like this you know am i the only unusual

03:30:39.520 --> 03:30:45.120
[Amit Varma]: person who's exactly like this and again i've done episodes on the caa and also radically

03:30:45.120 --> 03:30:49.000
[Amit Varma]: networked societies i link those from the show notes which that was a great example

03:30:49.000 --> 03:30:52.880
[Amit Varma]: of society and the state that also gave me a lot of hope so many young people not just

03:30:52.880 --> 03:30:58.320
[Amit Varma]: singing fairs but uh you know uh waving the preamble of the constitution on the streets

03:30:58.320 --> 03:31:02.040
[Amit Varma]: like who would have thunk of something like that a generation back though i wish they

03:31:02.040 --> 03:31:07.320
[Amit Varma]: had waved the ambedkar version and not the indira gandhi uh version with the word socialism

03:31:07.320 --> 03:31:13.000
[Amit Varma]: in it but regardless some preamble is better than no preamble my other question is about

03:31:13.000 --> 03:31:18.680
[Amit Varma]: politics now at at one point um in your book and i'll go back to your book just to uh sort

03:31:18.680 --> 03:31:23.000
[Amit Varma]: of get into the subject where uh you write about indira gandhi's role in this and you

03:31:23.000 --> 03:31:27.280
[Amit Varma]: say quote the deterioration was due to a large degree to indira gandhi's changed style of

03:31:27.280 --> 03:31:33.040
[Amit Varma]: politics the minorities had begun to move away from the congress i uh indira gandhi

03:31:33.040 --> 03:31:38.960
[Amit Varma]: made a bid for the hindu vote to the bjp's discomfort uh stop quote and i i did an episode

03:31:38.960 --> 03:31:45.920
[Amit Varma]: with vinay sitapati recently on uh you know the bjp before uh modi and shah so to say

03:31:45.920 --> 03:31:49.240
[Amit Varma]: and one of the things that emerges there is that the congress turned to the hindu vote

03:31:49.240 --> 03:31:53.880
[Amit Varma]: in a big way in the early 80s and the bjp had then uh you know when they were formed

03:31:53.880 --> 03:31:58.160
[Amit Varma]: vajpayee was saying all these flowery things about gandhi and socialism and all that but

03:31:58.160 --> 03:32:02.080
[Amit Varma]: they had to respond because the hindu vote was going away and therefore they responded

03:32:02.080 --> 03:32:06.400
[Amit Varma]: by getting more and more radical and uh you know and it became a race to the bottom and

03:32:06.400 --> 03:32:11.680
[Amit Varma]: of course the bjp won because uh you know the bottom was not a new place for them uh

03:32:11.680 --> 03:32:17.960
[Amit Varma]: so uh and and when i look at current times one of the things that disheartens me is that

03:32:17.960 --> 03:32:23.440
[Amit Varma]: uh that soft hindutva of the congress remains in a lot of what they do they did make kamal

03:32:23.440 --> 03:32:29.200
[Amit Varma]: jainath cm of uh madhya pradesh despite all their posturing on uh twitter they'll do that

03:32:29.200 --> 03:32:33.520
[Amit Varma]: soft hindutva thing they'll chase that vote you know when the temple judgment came they

03:32:33.520 --> 03:32:38.280
[Amit Varma]: actually said that uh you know uh it was rajiv gandhi who first opened the gates and all

03:32:38.280 --> 03:32:43.000
[Amit Varma]: of that you see the amadmi party uh chasing that also with the you know the chanting of

03:32:43.000 --> 03:32:47.600
[Amit Varma]: the hanuman chalisa after the last election and all of that and i think one realization

03:32:47.600 --> 03:32:52.920
[Amit Varma]: or at least one perception because it may not be true so i won't call it realization

03:32:52.920 --> 03:32:58.540
[Amit Varma]: but one perception which all these parties seem to have come to is that you cannot mess

03:32:58.540 --> 03:33:05.880
[Amit Varma]: with the hindu vote so uh does that put a limit on the politics that can happen on behalf

03:33:05.880 --> 03:33:12.000
[Amit Varma]: of the marginalized people uh in this country the fact that you know that there is a realization

03:33:12.000 --> 03:33:16.880
[Amit Varma]: among the parties or there is an perception among the parties because i don't believe

03:33:16.880 --> 03:33:20.480
[Amit Varma]: it's entirely true but there is a perception among the parties that you cannot piss off

03:33:20.480 --> 03:33:24.840
[Amit Varma]: the hindu vote which is why even when caa was happening right there in delhi you did

03:33:24.840 --> 03:33:29.640
[Amit Varma]: not see kejriwal besides making a few token noises really going out there and doing something

03:33:29.640 --> 03:33:34.080
[Amit Varma]: about it so now obviously it is true as i keep saying on the show that politics is downstream

03:33:34.080 --> 03:33:38.640
[Amit Varma]: of culture the culture has to change first then the politics will respond but uh you

03:33:38.640 --> 03:33:43.320
[Amit Varma]: know the culture is complicated it's got multitudes all of that but in a political sense is there

03:33:43.320 --> 03:33:48.880
[Amit Varma]: something that gives you hope someone who will actually fight against this because you

03:33:48.880 --> 03:33:53.600
[Amit Varma]: know despite the random twitter posturing the rahul gandhi may do on the ground the

03:33:53.600 --> 03:33:57.920
[Amit Varma]: congress doesn't give a shit they're playing the soft end of the game so what is your perception

03:33:57.920 --> 03:34:04.280
[Amit Varma]: of our politics the way it is and what it means for muslims see i think uh under the

03:34:04.280 --> 03:34:09.480
[Guest]: circumstances uh the soft hindutva would be acceptable to a large number of people because

03:34:09.480 --> 03:34:15.860
[Guest]: at least uh this doesn't result in everyday violence i mean congress has been done doing

03:34:15.860 --> 03:34:23.880
[Guest]: soft hindutva for decades but it didn't result in uh lynching of people and at least there

03:34:23.880 --> 03:34:30.000
[Guest]: was some token lip service uh after every riot and the government or the law enforcement

03:34:30.000 --> 03:34:35.240
[Guest]: agencies didn't really go after the victims in the way they do now i mean they actually

03:34:35.240 --> 03:34:39.380
[Guest]: frame the victims if a person is getting lynched his the charge sheet is filed against his

03:34:39.380 --> 03:34:47.720
[Guest]: family also so at least this sort of everyday terrorism of civilians was not uh there so

03:34:47.720 --> 03:34:55.440
[Guest]: probably we'll return to this happy coexistence of uh increasing hinduization of indian society

03:34:55.440 --> 03:35:00.600
[Guest]: which i think it very difficult to resist for the simple reason the majority is hindu

03:35:00.600 --> 03:35:06.400
[Guest]: and uh there is increased religiosity of our public spaces it's not just hindu religiosity

03:35:06.400 --> 03:35:12.160
[Guest]: but even muslims are becoming overtly i mean in their wherever their numerical strengths

03:35:12.160 --> 03:35:19.760
[Guest]: they are becoming overtly demonstrative about their identity or any other religion so that

03:35:19.760 --> 03:35:24.480
[Guest]: is something which is uh happening in our society probably some kind of churning is

03:35:24.480 --> 03:35:29.440
[Guest]: required and at some level we'll some point in time we'll realize that it is all stupidity

03:35:29.440 --> 03:35:38.120
[Guest]: and we'll go back to being normal human beings but if this fear of if this fear of the street

03:35:38.120 --> 03:35:44.880
[Guest]: goes away then probably more muslims can come out and claim part of this street right now

03:35:44.880 --> 03:35:51.160
[Guest]: one of the reasons why they are comfortable in moving to a ghetto though they don't get

03:35:51.160 --> 03:35:55.480
[Guest]: accommodation in a lot of places but even when the accommodation option is available

03:35:55.480 --> 03:36:00.280
[Guest]: a lot of them prefer to go to a ghetto is because they think it's safe for them and

03:36:00.280 --> 03:36:06.320
[Guest]: their children so once your streets are safer your public transportation is safer you'll

03:36:06.320 --> 03:36:11.880
[Guest]: see more people accessing it more people trying making an effort here more people asserting

03:36:11.880 --> 03:36:19.120
[Guest]: their rights here so that can probably over a period of time have a cascading effect on

03:36:19.120 --> 03:36:25.920
[Guest]: our society and our you know the culture as we know it and going back to what kefi has

03:36:25.920 --> 03:36:30.760
[Guest]: we had said that if every hindu has one or two muslim friends then if there are more

03:36:30.760 --> 03:36:36.080
[Guest]: muslims in public spaces and probably more hindus can find muslim friends and they'll

03:36:36.080 --> 03:36:45.720
[Guest]: learn to distinguish between what they perceived and what they find your very wise words i've

03:36:45.720 --> 03:36:49.880
[Amit Varma]: taken up a lot of your time so i'll end with a final question which has nothing to do either

03:36:49.880 --> 03:36:54.200
[Amit Varma]: with the book or the subject at hand but instead about you i'm always sort of awed when an

03:36:54.200 --> 03:36:59.440
[Amit Varma]: author writes a book like this because i think about just that process how it must have changed

03:36:59.440 --> 03:37:05.320
[Amit Varma]: that person because i think writing a serious book is always also a process of self-discovery

03:37:05.320 --> 03:37:10.160
[Amit Varma]: about learning things about yourself and all of that how did this book change you like

03:37:10.160 --> 03:37:14.880
[Amit Varma]: what are the big things you know now that you did not know before the book perhaps or

03:37:14.880 --> 03:37:18.200
[Amit Varma]: you know i mean what gave you the impetus to do a book like this and having done a book

03:37:18.200 --> 03:37:23.200
[Amit Varma]: like this you know what was the process like was it difficult was it hard at one point

03:37:23.200 --> 03:37:27.880
[Amit Varma]: you wrote about you know how your dad wasn't so comfortable about the personal bits of

03:37:27.880 --> 03:37:32.960
[Amit Varma]: you know your childhood and all of that but i think yesterday on twitter you wrote that

03:37:32.960 --> 03:37:37.800
[Amit Varma]: he said to you that he's very proud of the way that you've written about the whole subject

03:37:37.800 --> 03:37:42.600
[Amit Varma]: and indeed he should be because what a wonderful book so tell me a little bit about this process

03:37:42.600 --> 03:37:48.760
[Guest]: and what it's meant to you actually i think i was veering towards writing this book since

03:37:48.760 --> 03:37:55.600
[Guest]: i started this magazine called force in 2003 though it was a magazine on national security

03:37:55.600 --> 03:38:02.480
[Guest]: and defense and our focus was on the indian military and external defense at that time

03:38:02.480 --> 03:38:10.480
[Guest]: but that was also the time when this global war on terrorism was underway and we used

03:38:10.480 --> 03:38:15.640
[Guest]: to meet i mean when i used to go and meet people especially from the armed forces i

03:38:15.640 --> 03:38:23.440
[Guest]: used to hear constantly that about terrorism i used to travel a lot to kashmir my early

03:38:23.440 --> 03:38:32.440
[Guest]: reporting uh was always from kashmir and and i as i became more and more familiar with

03:38:32.440 --> 03:38:39.040
[Guest]: the insurgency and the antecedents of insurgency the problems that the people are facing there

03:38:39.040 --> 03:38:48.440
[Guest]: again the vilification which we see now in the mainstream the mainland india i started

03:38:48.440 --> 03:38:53.800
[Guest]: with kashmir i mean that is the people have been living with that for years so i i used

03:38:53.800 --> 03:38:59.320
[Guest]: to write when i used to come back and write my article in the magazine i used to bring

03:38:59.320 --> 03:39:08.040
[Guest]: in these elements about how rumors are spread how perceptions are deliberately built to

03:39:08.040 --> 03:39:16.120
[Guest]: actually dehumanize some people i mean uh my early earliest experience in kashmir was

03:39:16.120 --> 03:39:22.160
[Guest]: so uh traumatizing for me i mean though i was not at the receiving end but i was being

03:39:22.160 --> 03:39:29.720
[Guest]: driven to uh to a separatist leader's house by a local boy who wanted to become a journalist

03:39:29.720 --> 03:39:34.480
[Guest]: i had gone to the press colony to meet some people and one of the journalists said that

03:39:34.480 --> 03:39:39.840
[Guest]: my younger brother also wants to be a journalist and he wants to go to delhi and study journalism

03:39:39.840 --> 03:39:47.840
[Guest]: very young nice enthusiastic boy and he offered to drive me uh to this leader's house and

03:39:47.840 --> 03:39:59.200
[Guest]: while we were going there the car was stopped by a crpf guy who used his bait into we very

03:39:59.200 --> 03:40:07.680
[Guest]: violently uh bound the the engine the drum and he stopped the car and he spoke to this

03:40:07.680 --> 03:40:14.560
[Guest]: boy very harshly and this boy immediately minutes before was you know very enthusiastically

03:40:14.560 --> 03:40:19.080
[Guest]: telling me his plans and how he was going to finish school now and if i could help him

03:40:19.080 --> 03:40:27.520
[Guest]: and uh he was stopped violently and this guy he was scouring in fear i mean he was shaken

03:40:27.520 --> 03:40:33.960
[Guest]: up so badly he got out of the car and this constable was so insulting i also got out

03:40:33.960 --> 03:40:40.320
[Guest]: and i said why are you talking to him like this and he said madam up to pray here

03:40:40.320 --> 03:40:45.600
[Guest]: so i felt this everyday humiliation and this boy from that point till the rest of my journey

03:40:45.600 --> 03:40:49.760
[Guest]: he kept quiet he didn't say anything because obviously he felt so humiliated in front of

03:40:49.760 --> 03:40:54.200
[Guest]: somebody he was bragging about he was talking about how great he is and how well he's doing

03:40:54.200 --> 03:41:01.400
[Guest]: in school and so that was my first experience and then subsequently i used to see we are

03:41:01.400 --> 03:41:05.960
[Guest]: traveling someplace and i'm one fancy journalist from delhi so nobody would trouble me but

03:41:05.960 --> 03:41:10.800
[Guest]: uh the driver of the car would be harassed the taxi would be harassed at every checkpoint

03:41:10.800 --> 03:41:18.000
[Guest]: and every hundred meters there would be a checkpoint so that i i became more um engaged

03:41:18.000 --> 03:41:25.840
[Guest]: with their everyday struggle instead of the big picture of pakistan instigating violence

03:41:25.840 --> 03:41:32.680
[Guest]: or terrorism into india and while i was engaging with them more and more i came across a islamic

03:41:32.680 --> 03:41:38.200
[Guest]: sect la hadith my first encounter with the islamic sect was in kashmir because in delhi

03:41:38.200 --> 03:41:45.760
[Guest]: i have not been so exposed to the muslims or various strands of islam because i was

03:41:45.760 --> 03:41:50.640
[Guest]: not exposed to them when i was growing up in my work my career did not expose me to

03:41:50.640 --> 03:41:59.800
